[White "Introduction and Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Hello Chess-Lover! A warm welcome to my course: Crush the Caro-Kann.  In the Quickerstarter Guide, I will cover the most important variations and refer to the main chapters they belong to and where you can learn about them in more depth. I am thrilled to share all the variations with you. You will see some novelties and new concepts sprinkled throughout the course.   I designed the move trainer to get you tournament ready. There will be pawn structure sheets, thematic tactics and model game chapters, the Club Player chapter, and the Extensive Course Summary.    A little more about myself. I am FM Midas Ratsma from the Netherlands, working full-time as a chess author and coach. I published an attacking repertoire for Club Players for both colors, which has been received very well by the Chessable community. Also, I am the founder of the website @@LinkStart@@www.thechesscommunity.com@@LinkEnd@@ which is a place where chess players can connect for training games and lessons from passionate coaches. Currently, I am working on two more Chessable courses, a tactics course for Club Players and an opening course for beginners. }
2. d4 d5 { Black fights back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We will go for the Advance variation. The big critical test against the Caro-Kann, according to GM L'Ami who made the Lifetime Caro-Kann repertoire. }
3... Bf5
{ 3...c5  We will have an extensive look at the Khenkin-Arkell variation, which is getting more and more popular these days. }
4. g4
{ We will play the Bayonet Attack immediately harassing the bishop. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position. I was inspired to make this course as I saw the Bayonet attack was tried in the last two years by top GMs Dubov and Van Foreest, who have both been seconds for Carlsen's team in the world championship match. Also, it has been played multiple times by Top GMs Mamedyarov and the two-time Candidates winner Nepomniachtchi.   I believe the Bayonet Attack is a dynamic, attacking, and surprising opening, and it is currently an underestimated weapon at the tournament and Club Player level. }
