1. e4 c6
{ This course will be a full repertoire against the Caro-Kann. In this Quickstarter Guide, I will teach you a quick summary of the most important variations in the course and also refer to the corresponding chapters for more detailed coverage. }
2. d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5
{ The Khenkin-Arkell variation. Instead of the mainline  3...Bf5  , Black immediately targets White's center. This move is becoming increasingly popular and offers a sound way to fight the advanced variation. We will see plenty of novelties against this variation and show that this is a dangerous opening for Black when the opponent isn't super well-prepared. }
4. Nf3
{ We develop and protect the pawn!  4.dxc5  is more popular and a good alternative. The disadvantage is that Black can play  4...e6  5.Be3  Nd7  Threatening to win back the pawn. We can pin the knight with  6.Bb5  , however, after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5, targetting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nc6
{ Black develops and puts more pressure on the center. Now that Black played ...Nc6, their knight, cannot help anymore to regain the c5-pawn. That's why we capture on c5 now. }
5. dxc5 Bg4
{ As Black plays the Caro-Kann, they want to develop their light-squared bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
6. c3
{ A multi-purpose move, it gives us the option to stabilize our dark-squared bishop on the d4-square to hold on to the c5 and e5-pawns, but also allows us to safeguard our c5-pawn with b4. Furthermore, the open diagonal for the queen can come in handy as it allows Qb3 or Qa4. We also set up a sneaky trap as  6...Nxe5  immediately loses after  7.Nxe5  Bxd1  8.Bb5+  .  This famous trap occurs in many openings. }
6... e6 7. Be3 { Again  7...Nxe5  doesn't work since  8.Qa4+  wins the game. }
7... Bxf3
{ The most popular move in the database. It's bad for Black to give up on the light-squared bishop so easily. }
8. Qxf3
{ After the most popular move  8...Nxe5  , we will play  9.Bb5+  and gain a significant advantage after  9...Nc6  10.c4  .  Study more about this variation here.   Black's most critical reply is  8...Nge7  when we will also play  9.Bb5  pinning the knight to safeguard the e5-pawn. You can find this variation here. }
*

