3... c5
{ The Khenkin-Arkell variation. Instead of the mainline  3...Bf5  , Black immediately targets White's center. This move is becoming increasingly popular and offers a sound way to fight the advanced variation. We will see plenty of novelties against this variation and show that this is a dangerous opening for Black when the opponent isn't super well-prepared. }
4. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black develops and puts more pressure on the center. Now that Black played ...Nc6, their knight, cannot help anymore to regain the c5-pawn. That's why we capture on c5 now. }
5. dxc5 Bg4
{ As Black plays the Caro-Kann, they want to develop their light-squared bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
6. c3
{ A multi-purpose move, it gives us the option to stabilize our dark-squared bishop on the d4-square to hold on to the c5 and e5-pawns, but also allows us to safeguard our c5-pawn with b4. Furthermore, the open diagonal for the queen can come in handy as it allows Qb3 or Qa4. We also set up a sneaky trap as  6...Nxe5  immediately loses after  7.Nxe5  Bxd1  8.Bb5+  .  This famous trap occurs in many openings. }
