1. e4 c6
{ This course will be a full repertoire against the Caro-Kann. In this Quickstarter Guide, I will teach you a quick summary of the most important variations in the course and also refer to the corresponding chapters for more detailed coverage. }
2. d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5
{ The Khenkin-Arkell variation. Instead of the mainline  3...Bf5  , Black immediately targets White's center. This move is becoming increasingly popular and offers a sound way to fight the advanced variation. We will see plenty of novelties against this variation and show that this is a dangerous opening for Black when the opponent isn't super well-prepared. }
4. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black develops and puts more pressure on the center. Now that Black played ...Nc6, their knight, cannot help anymore to regain the c5-pawn. That's why we capture on c5 now. }
5. dxc5 e6
{ Black wants to regain the pawn with ...Bxc5! We played   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  with the idea that after  4...Nc6  , this knight can no longer help to regain the c5-pawn. So we will hold on to the pawn. }
6. Be3 { Developing and defending the pawn. } 6... Nge7
{ Black wants to play ...Nf5 and harass the bishop. When Black plays  6...Nh6  , we grab our chance to destroy the pawn structure with  7.Bxh6  when after  7...gxh6  we pin the knight with  8.Bb5  , study more about this variation here. }
7. Bd3
{ Preventing ...Nf5.  7.c3  is more popular for White, though after  7...Nf5  Black often gets the bishop pair and has decent compensation for the pawn. }
7... Ng6 8. Bb5
{ A cunning move, now that we don't need to defend against ...Nf5 anymore, we can find a more useful task for our bishop. This move has only been played four times. We are pinning the knight defending against ...Nxe5.  After  8...Bd7  , we can trade with  9.Bxc6  Bxc6  10.O-O  preparing to meet  10...Qc7  with  11.Re1  when we get a powerful initiative when Black would capture the e5-pawn. Study more about this variation here. }
