1. e4 c6
{ This course will be a full repertoire against the Caro-Kann. In this Quickstarter Guide, I will teach you a quick summary of the most important variations in the course and also refer to the corresponding chapters for more detailed coverage. }
2. d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5
{ The Khenkin-Arkell variation. Instead of the mainline  3...Bf5  , Black immediately targets White's center. This move is becoming increasingly popular and offers a sound way to fight the advanced variation. We will see plenty of novelties against this variation and show that this is a dangerous opening for Black when the opponent isn't super well-prepared. }
4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ A fascinating move played by Aronian, MVL, Grischuk, and many other top grandmasters. The idea is that our queen will be perfectly placed on f4 after being attacked by Black's knight. On f4 where it defends the e5-pawn and can put pressure on the kingside. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ Black gives up on the Caro-Kann dream to have the bishop outside the pawn chain. We call this locked-in bishop the bad French bishop. Without Black's bishop on f5, White's light-squared bishop is extremely dangerous on d3, where it's eyeing the h7-pawn. Black cannot safely castle. }
7. Nc3
{ This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3pP3/3Q4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.Qf4  move order. }
7... Nb4 { The main move, also recommended by L'Ami in his Caro-Kann course. }
8. Qd2
{ A novelty! We won't play  8.Bd3  and allow Black to exchange our powerful light-squared bishop with  8...Nxd3  .  Black has a French bad bishop pawn structure with their light-squared bishop locked in within the pawn chain. When we keep our light-squared bishop, it can be an extremely dangerous piece in the attack, after Black castles kingside.  It's important to know here that after a slow move from Black like @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  we will play  8.Bd3  and allow  8...Nb4  , since we can prevent our opponent from castling and gain a significant advantage after  9.Ne2  Nxd3+  10.cxd3  Ne7  11.Bd2  Ng6  12.Qg3  Be7  13.h4  h5  14.Nf4  , all these moves are explained in much more detail here.   In the variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nb4  , the same ideas wouldn't have worked when we also play  8.Bd3  Nxd3+  9.cxd3  Ne7  The same idea with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/4p3/3pP3/5Q2/2NP1N2/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne2  Ng6  11.Qg3  wouldn't work well as Black has counterplay with either  11...Qa5+  or  11...Bb4+  and also after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/4p3/3pP3/5Q2/2NP1N2/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Qg3  Be7  , we are too late with playing  12.h4  because of  12...Bxh4  .   Therefore, we will play the novelty @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nb4  8.Qd2  and after the slow @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nge7  or  7...h6  or  7...a6  go for  8.Bd3  . }
8... a6
{ Even though there are no games in this position, L'Ami has covered this in his Caro-Kann course and recommends this move. We will come up with our novelty versus his Caro-Kann course a couple of moves later. }
9. a3
{ We will kick the knight back and get ready to play Bd3 and develop the powerful bishop. }
9... Nc6 10. Bd3
{ With our bishop on d3, it's dangerous for Black to castle kingside. They should bring the knight to g6 to break the bishop's diagonal. Study more about how to put massive pressure on Black here. }
