[Black "Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 6...fxe6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This course will be a full repertoire against the Caro-Kann. In this Quickstarter Guide, I will teach you a quick summary of the most important variations in the course and also refer to the corresponding chapters for more detailed coverage. }
2. d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or Black has to play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  , which both allow us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Be4
{ Objectively, the best reply and the move suggested by L'Ami in his Chessable course on the Caro-Kann. }
5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The third most popular move in the position. We immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop. We don't want to play the popular  6.h4  h5  7.e6  Qd6  when Black is threatening ...Qg3+, and White struggles to equalize. }
6... fxe6 7. h4
{ Threatening h5, pushing the bishop back followed by f4 to completely lock in all Black's minor pieces on the kingside. }
7... h5 { The most critical reply, Black often goes wrong here already. } 8.
Bd3
{ Now Black weakened the light-squares with ...h5 it's the perfect time to exchange the bishops. }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qd6 { Black threatens ...Qg3+. } 10. Ne2
{ We develop and prevent ...Qg3+, also we get ready to develop with tempo with Bf4. After  10...e5  11.dxe5  Qxe5  , we can choose  12.Bf4  , covered here, where we force Black to play a couple of challenging moves but take a risk that we have to give a perpetual check.   The alternative is @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2p1p1/2p5/3pq2p/6PP/3Q1P2/PPP1N3/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qg6+  covered here, and we get a fighting middlegame.   After  10...Nd7  11.Qg6+  Kd8  12.Bg5  Black's pieces are stuck; with very accurate play, Black could find a way to free their pieces and reach an equal position, however, with one careless move, they could also end up in a dead lost position. You can study these variations here. }
*

