[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 6...Qd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This course will be a full repertoire against the Caro-Kann. In this Quickstarter Guide, I will teach you a quick summary of the most important variations in the course and also refer to the corresponding chapters for more detailed coverage. }
2. d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4 Be4 5. f3 Bg6 6. e6 Qd6 7. exf7+ Bxf7
{ When we reach this pawn structure, both sides have weaknesses. From Black's side, the e-pawn is weak. When Black can't trade the e-pawn, it will obstruct other pieces. On the other hand, White's pawns on the kingside are also weak, and f3 is not available for the knight. We plan to prevent Black from trading the e-pawn and castle queenside. }
8. Nc3 { Developing and preparing to castle queenside } 8... Nd7
{ Black develops and prepares ...e5! After  8...e5  9.dxe5  Qxe5  10.Nge2  We will develop with tempo with Bf4 and play Qd2 and O-O-O. }
9. f4
{ Preventing ...e5! It wasn't necessary to prevent ...e5 on the previous move since Black could only recapture with the queen, but now the knight can also recapture. After  9...g5  , I recommend  10.Nh3  not allowing Black the ...e5 break. Study this variation here. }
