{ This course will be a full repertoire against the Caro-Kann. In this Quickstarter Guide, I will teach you a quick summary of the most important variations in the course and also refer to the corresponding chapters for more detailed coverage. }
2. d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4 Bg6 5. e6 { We immediately want to shut down the dark-squared bishop. }
5... fxe6 6. h4 h5
{ Many other moves have been played, but when Black allows us to play h5, we will have an excellent position. }
7. Bd3 { We dominate the light squares. } 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3
{ We saw this same position with the pawn on f3 in the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq g3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  6.e6  fxe6  7.h4  h5  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  line however, there, the game continues in a different direction as  9...hxg4  10.Qg6+  Kd7  11.fxg4  would lead to a significant advantage for White.   Instead, Black played @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2p1p1/2pqp3/3p3p/3P2PP/3Q1P2/PPP5/RNB1K1NR w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  9...Qd6  there threatening ...Qg3+ which would be a losing move with the pawn on f2 since we can play @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2p1p1/2p1p3/3p3p/3P2PP/3Q4/PPP2P2/RNB1K1NR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qd6  9.Qg6+  Kd8  10.Nf3  going for the royal fork with Ne5-Nf7+. }
8... hxg4 9. Qg6+ { We give the check and grab back the pawn. } 9... Kd7 10.
Qxg4 Nf6 11. Qh3
{ Keeping an eye on the pinned e6-pawn. We threaten Nf3-Ne5, so Black has to defend against that. The computer also suggests  11.Qe2  as an alternative. I chose to recommend  11.Qh3  as we keep pressure on the pinned e6-pawn. Study more about this variation here. }
