{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4 Bg6 5. e6 { We immediately want to shut down the dark-squared bishop. }
5... Qd6 { Black threatens ...Qxe6 and forces us to trade the pawns. } 6. exf7+
Bxf7
{ We weaken the light-squares and create an outpost for our knight on e5! When we reach this pawn structure, both sides have weaknesses. From Black's side, the e-pawn is weak. When Black can't trade the e-pawn or move it forward, it will obstruct other pieces. For us, the g4-pawn can be a weakness. The pawn can come in handy, and we play g5 in some cases to stop the development of the knight. }
7. Nc3
{ This is a novelty. We play in the same style as from the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq g3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  6.e6  Qd6  7.exf7+  Bxf7  8.Nc3  variation with the only difference that the pawn is on f3 instead of f2. This informational line discusses all the differences and transpositions. A downside could be that the g4-pawn is not defended now; however, as the pawn is still on f2, we can also directly use the f3-square for the knight.   After  7...e5  , we will play  8.Nf3  and get a powerful knight after  8...e4  9.Ne5  , which is covered here.   When Black plays  7...Nd7  , we will go  8.f4  preventing ...e5 and transpose to a variation we already covered from the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq g3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  6.e6  Qd6  7.exf7+  Bxf7  8.Nc3  Nd7  9.f4  line here. }
