1. e4 c6
{ This course will be a full repertoire against the Caro-Kann. In this Quickstarter Guide, I will teach you a quick summary of the most important variations in the course and also refer to the corresponding chapters for more detailed coverage. }
2. d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4 Bd7
{ The third most popular move and a critical one. The problem for Black is when they play ...e6, they accept to have a bad 'French bishop' locked within the pawn chain. Having the pawn on g4 benefits us since Black cannot use the f5-square for the knight or bishop. Nevertheless, having the pawn on g4 could be a significant drawback in case the position opens up, as the pawn can be weak, and also, the squares on the kingside are weakened. Therefore our strategy is to prevent Black's break with ...c5 and keep the position closed. }
5. Nc3
{ I also considered  5.c4  , but we are overextended with White, and Black is doing fine after  5...e6  6.Nc3  c5  when the position opens up and our g4-pawn becomes weak.   5.Be3  would almost be the same as we transpose after  5...e6  6.Nc3  .   I chose to recommend  5.Nc3  , as in the variation with  5...h5  , we can benefit from delaying the bishop's development after  6.gxh5  Bf5  7.Nge2  Bg4  when  8.Bg5  pins the e7-pawn. }
5... e6 6. Be3
{ The plan is prophylactic; we play against the ...c5-break, which Black inevitably should play at some point. }
6... c5
{ Black goes for the pawn break directly. This is risky as Black has difficulties holding on to the pawn. }
7. dxc5 Qc7 { Black attacks the c5 and e5-pawns. } 8. Nb5
{ This will gain the bishop pair. } 8... Bxb5 9. Bxb5+ Nc6
{ Black threatens ...Qa5+ to win the bishop. } 10. c3
{ Preventing the fork with ...Qa5+ after  10...Qxe5  11.Nf3  Qc7  12.Qa4  we increase the pressure on the pinned knight. Study more about this variation here. }
