[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6 and 4...Bg4"]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann starts. Black prepares to strike in the center with ...d5. } 2.
d4 { We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5
{ The Khenkin-Arkell variation. Instead of the mainline  3...Bf5  , Black immediately targets White's center. This move is becoming increasingly popular and offers a sound way to fight the advanced variation. We will see plenty of novelties against this variation and show that this is a dangerous opening for Black when the opponent isn't super well-prepared. }
4. Nf3
{ We develop and protect the pawn!   4.dxc5  is more popular and a good alternative. The disadvantage is that Black can play  4...e6  5.Be3  Nd7  threatening to win back the pawn. We can pin the knight with  6.Bb5  , however, after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5, targetting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn. }
4... Bg4
{ 4...Bg4  and  4...Nc6  will most likely transpose to the same variation. After  4...Bg4  5.dxc5  Nc6  6.c3  or  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  Bg4  6.c3  , we have the same position. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  would give White an advanced French position with a tempo up after  5.c3! }
5. dxc5 e6
{ Black wants to play ...Nd7 and attack the c5 and e5-pawns. Usually, we transpose back with  5...Nc6  to the variation here. }
6. Bb5+ { This will force a pin when the knight blocks! } 6... Nd7 7. b4
{ We stay a pawn up! } 7... a5 8. c3
{ White is a pawn up, and at first sight, the computer gives an advantage for White. Black has a clear plan, though, to play ...Ne7-Nc6 and put pressure on the e5-pawn. }
8... Ne7 9. O-O Nc6 10. a3
{ A tricky move, it looks like a3 doesn't defend as the rook is pinned! } 10...
axb4 { A big mistake from Black. } 11. cxb4 Nxb4 12. Qd4 { Double attack! }
12... Nc2
{ Black forks the queen and rook! After  12...Bxf3  13.axb4  Rxa1  14.Qxa1  White is winning! }
13. Qxg4 Nxa1 14. Nd4
{ White is threatening Nxe6 and has a dominating position. The computer already gives +5. }
