1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5
{ We are going to have a look at the main move now, and after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  we capture the pawn. The reason we didn't capture immediately on move four is that after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxc5  e6  5.Be3  Black still can go  5...Nd7  harassing the c5-pawn. Even though we can play the pin with  6.Bb5  after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5 targeting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn.  Let's summarise some rules about how to play the pawn structure after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  before we get started with the variations.  1@@EndBracket@@ When White can comfortably hold on to the extra pawn, this should lead to a significant advantage  2@@EndBracket@@ Be3-Bd4 is a common idea to support both the c5 and e5 pawns  3@@EndBracket@@ We can trade light-squared bishop with Bb5, Bxc6 to eliminate the knight that is attacking our e5-pawn. A good line to show these three ideas is @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2PpP3/6b1/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nge7  8.Nbd2  Nf5  9.Bd4  to provide support to both the c5 and e5-pawns. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2PpPn2/3B2b1/2P2N2/PP1N1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nfxd4  Doesn't work since after  10.cxd4  Nxd4  11.Qa4+  we win a piece. So If Black continues with @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2PpPn2/3B2b1/2P2N2/PP1N1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be7  10.Bb5  O-O  11.Bxc6  , we succeed with our other plan to trade the knight and eliminate the attacker of the e5-pawn, and after  11...bxc6  12.O-O  we are a clean pawn up. You can find this variation here.  4@@EndBracket@@ c3-b4 is typically good, and we can advance the pawns on the queenside, and stabilize the c5-pawn. Also, c4-cxd5 can be powerful, giving Black an isolated d-pawn. An example line is the variation here.  5@@EndBracket@@ Often, we could also allow to sacrifice the e5-pawn and gain counterplay with quick development and ideas of Bd4 targetting the g7-pawn and Re1 developing with tempo. An example line is the variation here.   6@@EndBracket@@ After  5...e6  , Black locks in the bishop within the pawn chain and goes for a French bishop pawn structure. The same plans still apply, but one idea to be aware of is that after we go for plan 3 and eliminate the knight with Bxc6, Black plays ...Bxc6 we want to keep the bishop within the pawn chain by placing a knight on d4 as we see, for example, here @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppqb1p1p/2n1p2p/1BbpP3/8/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bxc6  , eliminating the knight which was attacking the e5-pawn  11...Bxc6  12.Ne2  . We prepare to place a knight on d4 to keep Black's light-squared bishop locked in within their pawn chain. After  12...O-O-O  13.Ned4  we have consolidated our knight on the d4-square, blocking Black's bishops, and can start attacking on the kingside. }
