[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6  with 7...Bxf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3
{ We develop and protect the pawn!   4.dxc5  is more popular and a good alternative. The disadvantage is that Black can play  4...e6  5.Be3  Nd7  threatening to win back the pawn. We can pin the knight with  6.Bb5  , however, after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5, targetting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nc6
{ Black develops and puts more pressure on the center. Now that Black played ...Nc6, they cannot play ...Nd7 anymore to regain the c5-pawn. That's why we capture on c5 now. }
5. dxc5 Bg4
{ As Black plays the Caro-Kann, they want to develop their light-squared bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
6. c3
{ A multi-purpose move, it gives us the option to stabilize our dark-squared bishop on the d4-square to hold on to the c5 and e5-pawns, but also allows us to safeguard our c5-pawn with b4. Furthermore, the open diagonal for the queen can come in handy as it allows Qb3 or Qa4. We also set up a sneaky trap as  6...Nxe5  immediately loses after  7.Nxe5  Bxd1  8.Bb5+  .  This famous trap occurs in many openings. }
6... e6 7. Be3
{ Again  7...Nxe5  doesn't work since  8.Qa4+  Qd7  9.Bb5  wins the game. }
7... Bxf3
{ The most popular move. It's bad for Black to give up on the light-squared bishop so easily. }
8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ { Developing with a check! } 9... Nc6 10. c4
{ Increasing the pressure on the center. White is already doing great. } 10...
Qf6 { Black's only move, going for a queen trade to release the tension. } 11.
Nd2
{ Developing and safeguarding the queen. White keeps a strong lead in development and has a significant advantage. Black cannot grab the poisoned pawn with  11...Qxb2  since after  12.Rb1  White further increases its lead in development, and Black won't survive with the king in the middle. }
