[White "1a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6 and 4...Bg4"]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6 with 7...Nge7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 Nge7
{ Black plans to play ...Nf5-Nxe3, we don't have to be worried about that as we can reply to ...Nf5 with Bd4. }
8. Nbd2 { Watch how GM Inarkiev won versus WGM Fuchs in this model game. } 8...
Nf5 9. Bd4
{ We prevent ...Nxe3 and hold on to the c5-pawn.  9...Nfxd4  10.cxd4  Nxd4  loses a piece after  11.Qa4+  . }
9... Be7 10. Bb5
{ In this pawn structure, it's best to use our bishop to eliminate the knight to get rid of one of the attackers on e5. Ideas with  10.h3  , doesn't force Black to trade their bishop since after  10...Bh5  11.g4  , they can still play  11...Nfxd4  to avoid losing a piece. }
10... O-O 11. Bxc6
{ We like to trade the knight to release the pressure against our center. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O
{ White is a clean pawn up! Black would like to pressure the c5-pawn with ...a5, ...Qc7-Qa7. With White, we want to stabilize with b3, avoiding counterplay against the b2-pawn. And when Black targets the c5-pawn, we want to be ready to play h3-g4 and force Black to trade on d4 so that we maintain a pawn up. A sample line is  12...a5  13.b3  Qc7  14.h3  Bh5  15.Re1  Qa7  16.g4  Nxd4  17.cxd4  With the trade, we secured the c5-pawn and stay a healthy pawn up. Black's bishop pair doesn't compensate the pawn since Black's dark-squared bishop is passive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6 and 4...Bg4"]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6 with 7...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 a6
{ Black wants to stop Bb5 permanently. } 8. Qb3
{ We unpin the knight and go directly for the b7-pawn. When Black defends this pawn with  8...Qc7  , we will reach a significant advantage after  9.Nbd2  when we stay a pawn up. If we would have played @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2PpP3/6b1/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nbd2  directly, our knight would still be pinned, so Black could win back the pawn there with  8...Nxe5  .  And as Black played ...a6 this time  9.Qa4+  doesn't win a piece after  9...Qd7  counterattacking the queen. }
8... Bxf3 9. Qxb7 { With a double attack on the knight and bishop! } 9... Na5
{ This move looks obvious for Black as they win a piece. It's a mistake as White has more then enough compensation. }
10. Qb4
{ Brilliant White will regain the piece after  10...Bh5  11.Qa4+  Ke7  12.Qh4+  we fork the king and the bishop. After  10...Be4  11.Qa4+  Ke7  12.Nd2  White will play b4 next, and Black's position is falling apart. }
10... d4 { Black's only move. } 11. gxf3 dxe3 12. Qa4+
{ We give a powerful intermediate check to misplace Black's king. } 12... Ke7
13. fxe3
{ White has more than enough compensation for the piece. Black's king and pieces on the kingside are misplaced. }
13... Qc7
{ Black wants to play ...Qxc5 followed by ...Qxe3+ and ...Qxe5 when they win three pawns and defend the knight again. We should prevent this and defend the e5-pawn. }
14. f4 Qxc5 15. Nd2
{ A fantastic move allowing  15...Qxe3+  since after  16.Be2  , the knight on a5 is hanging. }
15... Qxe3+ 16. Be2 Rd8 { Black goes for counterplay and threatens ...Qxd2+. }
17. Nf3 Qb6 18. Nd4
{ We threaten Qxa5+ winning the knight when after ...Qxa5+ Nxc6+ wins the queen. White has a winning position. }
