1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 a6
{ Black wants to stop Bb5 permanently. } 8. Qb3
{ We unpin the knight and go directly for the b7-pawn. When Black defends this pawn with  8...Qc7  , we will reach a significant advantage after  9.Nbd2  when we stay a pawn up. If we would have played @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2PpP3/6b1/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nbd2  directly, our knight would still be pinned, so Black could win back the pawn there with  8...Nxe5  .  And as Black played ...a6 this time  9.Qa4+  doesn't win a piece after  9...Qd7  counterattacking the queen. }
8... Bxf3 9. Qxb7 { With a double attack on the knight and bishop! } 9... Nge7
{ The most critical move which has only been played twice so far. } 10. gxf3
Ra7 11. Qb6
{ Keeping an eye on the rook to prevent Black from playing ...Nxe5  . } 11...
Qa8 { By protecting the knight, Black prepares ...Nf5-Nxe3. } 12. Nd2
{ We want to get the knight to b3 to support the c5-pawn. } 12... Nf5
{ Another option for Black is  12...Nxe5  , after which we play  13.Qa5  .  Whenever Black gets ready to castle and plays ...Be7, we will go for Qa4+. The variation could continue with  13...Nf5  14.O-O-O  Be7  15.Qa4+  . }
13. Nb3 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Be7 15. Nd4
{ We force Black to capture on e5 but, in return, gain control of the c6-square!  15...Bh4?  16.Kd2  would greatly improve our position as the bishop is no longer attacking the c5-pawn. }
15... Nxe5 16. f4 Nd7 17. Qc6
{ As our king is weaker, we force the trade of queens. Black can hold the balance with  17...Bxc5  18.Qxa8  when we reach an equal endgame. After  18...Rxa8  , we will advance our pawns on the queenside and start with  19.b4  .  We want to play a4 and Kd2 and put pressure with our queenside majority. }
