{ In the previous chapter, we already discussed this pawn structure and plans. Black wants to regain the pawn with ...Bxc5! We played @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  with the idea that after  4...Nc6  , this knight can no longer help to regain the c5-pawn. So we will hold on to the pawn. }
6. Be3
{ Developing and defending the pawn. Typically Black has two different plans either ...Ne7-Nf5 or ...Nh6-Nf5/Ng4. }
6... Nh6 7. Bxh6
{ We grab our chance and destroy Black's pawn structure.  7.Bd3  to prevent ...Nf5 wouldn't help as Black can play  7...Ng4  attacking the bishop and the e5-pawn. }
7... gxh6 8. Bb5
{ Pinning to lessen the pressure on the e5-pawn. Black will typically play for a queenside castle and try to attack us on the kingside. They don't want to castle kingside with the broken pawn structure. }
8... Bxc5 9. O-O Bd7
{ Black threatens to win a pawn with ...Nxe5; we will develop and defend the bishop. This position can also be reached by the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3p1p/2n1p2p/1BPpP3/8/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN1QK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bd7  9.O-O  Bxc5  move order. }
10. Nc3 Qc7 11. Bxc6
{ A typical idea in this position! Black has the bad French bishop, so we want to eliminate the c6-knight and stabilize one of our knights on the d4-square. }
11... Bxc6 12. Ne2
{ Preparing to place a knight on d4 to keep Black's light-squared bishop locked in within their pawn chain. }
12... O-O-O 13. Ned4
{ We have consolidated our knight on the d4-square, blocking Black's bishops, and can start attacking on the kingside. }
