6. Be3
{ Developing and defending the pawn. Typically Black has two different plans either ...Ne7-Nf5 or ...Nh6-Nf5/Ng4. }
6... Nh6 7. Bxh6
{ We grab our chance and destroy Black's pawn structure.  7.Bd3  to prevent ...Nf5 wouldn't help as Black can play  7...Ng4  attacking the bishop and the e5-pawn. }
7... gxh6 8. Bb5
{ Pinning to lessen the pressure on the e5-pawn. Black will typically play for a queenside castle and try to attack us on the kingside. They don't want to castle kingside with the broken pawn structure. }
8... Bxc5 9. O-O Bd7
{ Black threatens to win a pawn with ...Nxe5; we will develop and defend the bishop. This position can also be reached by the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3p1p/2n1p2p/1BPpP3/8/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN1QK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bd7  9.O-O  Bxc5  move order. }
10. Nc3 Rg8
{ After all other moves, we have the positional idea to trade on c6 and play Ne2-Ned4. If we would play  11.Bxc6  Bxc6  12.Ne2  , now Black will grab the chance to open the position with  12...d4  and create a dangerous attack. }
11. Qd3
{ We are getting ready to consolidate the position with either Ne2-Bxc6-Nd4 or Bxc6-Nb5-Nd4. Once we get a stable knight on d4, we block both bishops and keep a significant advantage due to the better pawn structure. It doesn't work yet to try and consolidate with  11.Bxc6  Bxc6  12.Ne2  since after  12...d4  Black gets a dangerous initiative. }
