[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6 5...e6 6...Nge7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5 e6
{ In the previous chapter, we already discussed this pawn structure and plans. Black wants to regain the pawn with ...Bxc5! We played @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  with the idea that after  4...Nc6  , this knight can no longer help to regain the c5-pawn. So we will hold on to the pawn. }
6. Be3
{ Developing and defending the pawn. Typically Black has two different plans either ...Ne7-Nf5 or ...Nh6-Nf5/Ng4. }
6... Nge7 7. Bd3
{ Preventing ...Nf5.  7.c3  is more popular for White, though after  7...Nf5  Black often gets the bishop pair and has decent compensation for the pawn. }
7... Ng6 8. Bb5
{ A cunning move. Now Black decided not to play ...Nf5 the bishop is no longer useful on d3. We move the bishop twice in a row. This move has only been played four times. We are pinning the knight, so we are defending against ...Nxe5. }
8... Qc7 9. O-O { We castle and challenge Black to grab the pawn. } 9... Nxe5
{ Capturing the e5-pawn is risky for Black when they have to recapture with the queen as we can gain a massive lead in development. After  9...Be7  , we have many ways to play and could go for  10.Bxc6  Qxc6  11.Nbd2  Bxc5  12.Bxc5  Qxc5  13.Nb3  when we have the typical French pawn structure where Black has the bad bishop.   9...Bd7  is the main move and transposes to the variation here. }
10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. c4
{ We threaten to break open the center with a favorable pawn trade. White is doing great here, and Black is underdeveloped. }
11... dxc4 12. Na3
{ Black is underdeveloped. We threaten Nxc4 to gain a tempo on the queen with a winning position. }
