{ What strategical plan do we have to improve our position? } 15. a3
{ An important move! We prepare b4 to safeguard the c5-pawn. We will drive Black's queen back and free the knight from the obligation to defend the bishop. As we have the bishop pair and pressure on the d5-pawn, our position is winning.  It's interesting that in a variation like  15...a6  16.Ba4  Rad8  17.b4  Qc7  the obvious  18.Nxd5  gives White a significant advantage; however, it allows Black some counterplay with  18...Nxd5  19.Rxd5  Ne5  20.Qe4  Rxd5  21.Qxd5  Ng4  . It's even stronger to first improve the position more with  @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/1pq1bppp/p1n2n2/2Pp4/BP6/P1N1BQ2/5PPP/R2R2K1 w - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Rac1  , as we will win the pawn anyway. Black could try  18...d4  19.Bf4  Qc8  20.Ne2  , but we will win the pawn and reach a winning position. }
