[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6/Bg4 Tactics and Model Games"]
[Black "Exercise 5: Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkbnr/1p3ppp/p1n1p3/2PpP3/8/1QP1Bb2/PP3PPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black just captured our knight on f3. Should we recapture, or do we have other plans? }
9. Qxb7 { With a double attack on the knight and bishop! } 9... Na5
{ This move looks obvious for Black as they win a piece. It's a mistake, as White has more than enough compensation.  Black's only good move,  9...Nge7  , has only been played in two out of the ten games that reached this position. This has been covered here.  9...d4  transposes after  10.gxf3  Na5  11.Qb4  . }
10. Qb4
{ Brilliant! White will regain the piece after  10...Bh5  11.Qa4+  Ke7  12.Qh4+  we fork the king and the bishop.   After  10...Be4  11.Qa4+  Ke7  12.Nd2  White will play b4 next, and Black's position is falling apart. }
10... d4 { Black's only move. } 11. gxf3 dxe3 12. Qa4+
{ We give a powerful intermediate check to misplace Black's king. } 12... Ke7
13. fxe3
{ White has more than enough compensation for the piece Black's king, and pieces on the kingside are misplaced. }
13... Qc7
{ We already have a significant advantage, but it doesn't mean that the position is easy yet. Black wants to play ...Qxc5 followed by ...Qxe3+ and ...Qxe5 when they win three pawns and defend the knight again. We should prevent this and defend the e5-pawn. }
14. f4 Qxc5 15. Nd2
{ A fantastic move allowing  15...Qxe3+  since after  16.Be2  , the knight on a5 is hanging. }
15... Qxe3+ 16. Be2 Rd8 { Black goes for counterplay and threatens ...Qxd2+. }
17. Nf3 Qb6 18. Nd4
{ We threaten Qa5+ winning the knight when after ...Qxa5+ Nxc6+ wins the queen. White has a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6/Bg4 Tactics and Model Games"]
[Black "Exercise 6: Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k1r1/ppqb1p1p/2n1p2p/1BbpP3/8/2NQ1N2/PPP2PPP/R4RK1 w q - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black is ready to castle queenside and consolidate. How do we strike before that happens? }
12. Bxc6 { First, we eliminate the annoying knight. } 12... Bxc6 13. Nb5 Bxb5
{ After  13...Qb6  we consolidate with  14.Nbd4  and White has a winning position. Typically Black can never grab the b2-pawn with the queen since our rook will get active along the b-file after  14...Qxb2  15.Rfb1  Qa3  16.Qxh7+  Black is in massive trouble. }
14. Qxb5+
{ This is much more comfortable for White as our king is safe. When we play c3, g3, Kg2, we safeguard the c-pawn and get out of the pin on the f2-pawn. White has no weaknesses, whereas Black has a weakened pawn structure on the kingside and can no longer castle. White has a significant advantage. After  14...Qc6  we avoid the trade of queens as our king is safer and play  15.Qd3  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6/Bg4 Tactics and Model Games"]
[Black "Exercise 7: Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/2n1p3/2PpP3/8/4BN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How can we prevent our opponent's plan? } 7. Bd3
{ Preventing ...Nf5.  7.c3  is more popular for White, though after  7...Nf5  Black often gets the bishop pair and has decent compensation for the pawn. }
7... Ng6 8. Bb5
{ A cunning move using prophylaxis again. Now that Black decided not to play ...Nf5, the bishop is no longer useful on d3. We move the bishop twice in a row. This move has only been played four times. We are pinning the knight, so we are defending against ...Nxe5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6/Bg4 Tactics and Model Games"]
[Black "Model Game: Antipov-Usmanov 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between GM Mikhail Antipov  (2597)  and IM Vasily Usmanov  (2472)  in 2018 in St Petersburg. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5
{ Antipov uses a different move order than in the course. We will start with  4.Nf3  , which has been explained in the course.  4.dxc5 is more popular and a good alternative. The disadvantage is that Black can play  4...e6  5.Be3  Nd7  Threatening to win back the pawn. We can pin the knight with  6.Bb5  , however, after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5, targetting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ We transpose back to the theory in the course where we played @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.dxc5  . }
5... Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Nc6 10. c4 Nf6 11. Nc3
{ We covered everything in the course till here. } 11... Rc8 12. cxd5
{ We give Black an isolated d5-pawn, which we have also seen after @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/1BPp4/2P5/2N1BQ2/PP3PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Be7  12.cxd5  exd5  in the course. }
12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 exd5 15. O-O-O
{ Immediately putting pressure on the d5-pawn. } 15... Rd8 16. Rd2
{ Preparing to double the rooks on the d-file. } 16... Ke7 17. Rhd1 Ke6 18. Bc4
{ A brilliant move since after the trade White gets a powerful pin on the bishop. After  18...Ne7  19.b4  g6  20.Bb3  Bg7  21.Re2  White also has a crushing advantage. }
18... dxc4 19. Rxd8 Nxd8 20. Rxd8 g6 21. Rb8 Kd5 22. Rxb7
{ The direct approach! White could also have played  23.Kc2  to threaten Bh6 and keep the deadly pin. }
22... Bxc5 23. Bxc5 Kxc5 24. Rxf7
{ White is a pawn up and also has a much more active rook. } 24... a5 25. Kd2
a4 26. Kc3 a3 27. Rc7+ Kd5 28. Rxc4 axb2 29. Rb4
{ Winning the b-pawn and the game! The rest is a matter of technique. } 29...
Re8 30. Rxb2 Kc5 31. Kd3 Re1 32. Re2 Rh1 33. h3 Kd5 34. Ke3 g5 35. f4 Ke6 36.
Kf2+ Kf5 37. Re1
{ Great endgame technique. Antipov sacrifices the f4-pawn to trade rooks and reach a winning pawn endgame. }
37... Rxe1 38. Kxe1 Kxf4 39. Ke2 Ke4 40. a4
{ A flawless win from Antipov who crushes his opponent from the opening. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6/Bg4 Tactics and Model Games"]
[Black "Model Game: Inarkiev-Fuchs 2012"]
[Result "*"]

{ This model game was played between GM Ernesto Inarkiev  (2683)  and WGM Juditch Fuchs  (2292)  in 2012 in Schaebisch, Germany. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. dxc5 Nc6 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 Nge7 8. Nbd2
{ Everything is covered till here. } 8... Ng6
{ A mistake as Black can't win the e5-pawn. As we saw  8...Nf5  would have been better when we play  9.Bd4  to prevent ...Nxe3 and hold on to the c5-pawn. }
9. Qa4 { Pinning the knight and attacking the bishop! } 9... Bxf3
{ Black is forced to make this trade that benefits White. } 10. Nxf3 Be7 11.
Bb5 { Increasing the pressure on the pinned knight. } 11... O-O
{ Allowing White to win a pawn on c6.  11...Qc7  wouldn't be much better since after  12.O-O  O-O  White can play  13.Bxc6  a typical motif eliminating the attacker of the e5-pawn, and after  13...bxc6  White stabilizes with  14.Bd4  and has a clean pawn up. }
12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Bd4
{ This typical motif we have seen before here and in the model game here.  13.Qxc6  would run into  13...Qb8  attacking the b2 and e5-pawns. White would still be better there, but there is no need for White to capture on c6. }
13... Qc7
{ If Black would have played @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp2bppp/2n1p1n1/1BPpP3/Q7/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qc7  the same position could have been reached after  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Bd4  O-O  . }
14. O-O f5 15. b4 { This is a useful move giving more support to the c5-pawn. }
15... Nh8
{ Black desperately tries to create some counterplay, but the knight on the corner looks awful. }
16. Rab1 a6 17. Be3
{ Inarkeiev wants to free the d4-square for the knight. One problem is that the bishop is no longer protecting the e5-pawn. The computer suggests the elegant  17.c4  dxc4  18.Ba1  preparing for Nd4 to harass the c6 and e6-pawns. }
17... Rfc8
{ Stronger would have been  17...f4  chasing the bishop when after  18.Bd2  Black can try to fight back with  18...a5  . And after  19.Nd4  axb4  20.Qxc6  Qxc6  21.Nxc6  Bxc5  22.cxb4  the endgame should still be winning for White. }
18. Nd4 { The knight is amazing on the d4-square attacking c6 and e6. } 18...
Kf7 19. f4
{ White stabilizes the position and is a pawn-up with also a big space advantage. }
19... Ng6 20. Qc2 Nf8 21. g4
{ A powerful pawn sacrifice. After  21...fxg4  , White will rip apart Black's king's position with  22.f5  . }
21... g6 22. gxf5 gxf5 23. Nxf5
{ White's pawns will be unstoppable in the attack. } 23... exf5 24. Qxf5+ Ke8
25. Qh5+ Kd7 26. Qh3+ Ne6 27. Rbe1
{ Also, the direct  27.f5  would be winning for White after  27...Qxe5  28.fxe6+  Qxe6  29.Qxe6+  Kxe6  30.Rbe1  . }
27... Rg8+ 28. Kh1 Qd8 29. f5 Ng5 30. Bxg5 Bxg5 31. f6+ Kc7 32. Qxh7+ Kb8 33.
e6 { Black has no counterplay and the pawns are almost queening. } 33... Bxf6
34. e7 Bxe7 35. Rxe7
{ A fantastic win from Inarkiev who dominated the game from the opening. } *

