[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...cxd4"]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...cxd4 with 6...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4
{ The second most popular move. Black wants to avoid the position after  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  , where Black had a tough time regaining the pawn. }
5. Qxd4
{ A fascinating move played by Aronian, MVL, Grischuk, and many other top grandmasters. The idea is that our queen is perfectly placed on f4, where it defends the e5-pawn and can put pressure on the kingside. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 g6
{ Black prepares ...Bh6 threatening the queen and bishop on c1. } 7. Nc3
{ Developing and preparing to castle queenside and opening the rook to defend on c1. }
7... Bg7 { This logical move is a big mistake. } 8. Be3
{ Preventing ...d4 and getting ready to castle queenside. } 8... Nh6 9. O-O-O
e6 { Black has to defend the d5-pawn, which weakens the dark squares. } 10. g4
{ Shutting down the knight on h6 and also creating the opportunity to play g5 and prevent Black's only break in the position with ...f6. }
10... O-O 11. g5 { Preventing the ...f6 break. } 11... Nf5
{ Black is threatening ...Qc7 and would have a fantastic position if they win the e5-pawn. }
12. Ne4
{ A great idea. We want to play Nf6+ to weaken Black's king and block the bishop's diagonal to avoid losing the e5-pawn. Afterward, we can start marching our h-pawn and go for a kingside attack. White is winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...cxd4"]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...cxd4 with 6...g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4
{ The second most popular move. Black wants to avoid the position after  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  , where Black had a tough time regaining the pawn. }
5. Qxd4
{ A fascinating move played by Aronian, MVL, Grischuk, and many other top grandmasters. The idea is that our queen is perfectly placed on f4, where it defends the e5-pawn and can put pressure on the kingside. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 g6
{ Black prepares ...Bh6 threatening the queen and bishop on c1. } 7. Nc3
{ Developing and preparing to castle queenside and opening the rook to defend on c1. }
7... d4 { The critical try! } 8. Nb5
{ 8.Bc4  is an alternative played by MVL, I don't like that after  8...Bf5  9.Nb5  Black can play  9...Rc8  and create counterplay against the bishop preventing us from capturing on d4. }
8... Bh6 9. Qh4 Bxc1 10. Rxc1 a6
{ Forces us to capture on d4 when Black can regain the e5-pawn, which they indirectly protect with the idea of ...Qa5+. }
11. Nbxd4 Nxe5 12. Be2
{ 12.Nxe5  is also playable however it runs into  12...Qa5+  13.c3  Qxe5+  when Black regains the piece. }
12... Nxf3+
{ We want to recapture with the knight since after  13.Bxf3  e5  Black can force a queen trade and should be fine in the endgame. }
13. Nxf3
{ Black should be able to finish development without too much trouble. White has a slightly better pawn structure because of the three versus two on the queenside. After  13...Qb6  14.b3  Nf6  15.O-O  O-O  16.Rfe1  White can start targeting the e7-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...cxd4"]
[Black "Pawn structure and plans 4...cxd4 with 6...e6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ By far the main move in the position, supporting the center, opening the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop but also locking in the light-squared bishop. }
7. Nc3
{ We reach the French Bad bishop pawn structure. This is the structure where Black's light-squared bishop is locked in within the pawn chain. The structure typically arises from the French opening but can also occur in the Caro-Kann.   1@@EndBracket@@ We plan to trade all minor pieces except the bad French bishop.   2@@EndBracket@@ The d4-square is the perfect place for the knight.   3@@EndBracket@@ The g7-pawn is a juicy target. So we often like to play Qg3. Harassing the pawn can also slow Black's development when the bishop has to wait on f8 and cannot develop. Black's knight on the kingside is a good defender when it plays to ...Nge7, ...Ng6, but we can harass it with the h4, Nge2-Nf4, as shown here. Also, we can often trade the knight when it comes to f5 as well.   4@@EndBracket@@ The light-squared bishop is powerful on d3 in the attack. After  7...Nb4  We will play the novelty  8.Qd2  keeping the bishop alive and after the slow  7...Nge7  or  7...h6  or  7...a6  go for  8.Bd3  .   The logic behind plan 4 is as follows: When Black plays a slow move like @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  we will play  8.Bd3  and allow  8...Nb4  , since we can prevent our opponent from castling and gain a significant advantage after  9.Ne2  Nxd3+  10.cxd3  Ne7  11.Bd2  Ng6  12.Qg3  Be7  13.h4  h5  14.Nf4  . All these moves are explained in much more detail here.   In the variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nb4  , the same ideas wouldn't have worked after  8.Bd3  Nxd3+  9.cxd3  Ne7  As we didn't castle yet @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/4p3/3pP3/5Q2/2NP1N2/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne2  Ng6  11.Qg3  wouldn't work well as Black has counterplay with either  11...Qa5+  or  11...Bb4+  and also after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/4p3/3pP3/5Q2/2NP1N2/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Qg3  Be7  , we are too late with playing  12.h4  because of  12...Bxh4  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...cxd4"]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...cxd4 6...e6 with 7...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4
{ The second most popular move. Black wants to avoid the position after  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  , where Black had a tough time regaining the pawn. }
5. Qxd4
{ A fascinating move played by Aronian, MVL, Grischuk, and many other top grandmasters. The idea is that our queen is perfectly placed on f4, where it defends the e5-pawn and can put pressure on the kingside. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ Black locks in the light-squared bishop in the pawn chain.  Usually, the typical Caro-Kann idea is to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6. When the bishop is inside the pawn chain, Black has a bad French bishop. This makes our light-squared bishop extremely dangerous on d3, where it's eyeing at the h7-pawn. Black cannot safely castle.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3pP3/3Q4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.Qf4  move order. }
7. Nc3 a6 8. Bd3
{ As Black is playing slow, we continue development and allow them to trade our light-squared bishop with ...Nb4-Nxd3. }
8... Qc7 { Black prepares ...Ne7-Ng6 going after the e5-pawn. } 9. O-O
{ We get ready to play Re1 } 9... Nge7 10. Re1 Ng6 11. Qg3
{ This time, we don't want to play ...Bxg6 because we can keep the powerful bishop for the attack and start harassing the knight with h4-h5. In the position here, I recommend ...Bxg6 to release the pressure on the e5-pawn. Watch how IM Dai crushed GM Lin from this position in the model game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Khenkin-Arkell 4...cxd4"]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...cxd4 6...e6 with 7...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4
{ The second most popular move. Black wants to avoid the position after  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  , where Black had a tough time regaining the pawn. }
5. Qxd4
{ A fascinating move played by Aronian, MVL, Grischuk, and many other top grandmasters. The idea is that our queen is perfectly placed on f4, where it defends the e5-pawn and can put pressure on the kingside. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ Black locks in the light-squared bishop in the pawn chain.  Usually, the typical Caro-Kann idea is to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6. When the bishop is inside the pawn chain, Black has a bad French bishop. This makes our light-squared bishop extremely dangerous on d3, where it's eyeing at the h7-pawn. Black cannot safely castle.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3pP3/3Q4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.Qf4  move order. }
7. Nc3 a6 8. Bd3
{ As Black is playing slow, we continue development and allow them to trade our light-squared bishop with ...Nb4-Nxd3. }
8... Nb4 9. Ne2
{ The idea will become clear a couple of moves later! Black should develop with ...Ne7-Ng6 to secure the g7-pawn. We can attack the knight there with Nf4. }
9... Nxd3+ 10. cxd3 Ne7 11. Bd2
{ We want to delay  11.O-O  , because after  11...Ng6  12.Qg3  Be7  we now cannot play  13.h4  as the rook is no longer on the h-file and  13...Bxh4  will be played. }
11... Ng6 12. Qg3
{ The queen is placed very well on g3 and puts pressure on the g7-pawn. } 12...
Be7 13. h4 { Threatening h5. } 13... h5 { Preventing h5. } 14. Nf4
{ Black runs into big trouble as we will exchange the knight that holds together the position. }
14... Nxf4 15. Bxf4 Bb4+
{ Black gives a check, desperately looking for counterplay. } 16. Ke2
{ A classy move, connecting the rooks. Our king won't be in any danger as we can play Rhc1 and Kf1 with an artificial castle. Because of the pressure on g7 and the bad French bishop White has a winning position. }
*

