[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4
{ The second most popular move. Black wants to avoid the position after  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  , where Black had a tough time regaining the pawn. }
5. Qxd4
{ A fascinating move played by Aronian, MVL, Grischuk, and many other top grandmasters. The idea is that our queen is perfectly placed on f4, where it defends the e5-pawn and can put pressure on the kingside. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ Black locks in the light-squared bishop in the pawn chain.  Usually, the typical Caro-Kann idea is to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6. When the bishop is inside the pawn chain, Black has a bad French bishop. This makes our light-squared bishop extremely dangerous on d3, where it's eyeing at the h7-pawn. Black cannot safely castle.  This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3pP3/3Q4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.Qf4  move order. }
7. Nc3 h6 { Not so critical, but it has been played by Chinese superstar Wei. }
8. Bd3 { We can continue in a similar style as after ...a6. } 8... Nb4 9. O-O
Nxd3 10. cxd3 Ne7 11. Ne2
{ Using the same idea to exchange the knight! We can exchange Black's knight regardless of whether it jumps with ...Ng6 or ...Nf5. }
11... Ng6 12. Qg3
{ We will play Nf4 next, and Black is in a difficult position. } *

