[White "2b) Khenkin-Arkell 4...cxd4 Tactics and Model Games"]
[Black "Model Game: Dai-Lin"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between IM Changren Dai  (2506)  and GM Chen lin  (2489)  in Tianjin-Jiangsu, China in 2021. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qf4 e6 7. Nc3 a6 8. Bd3
Qc7 9. O-O Nge7 10. Re1 Ng6 11. Qg3
{ Everything has been covered here, and White is already doing great! } 11...
Nb4 12. h4
{ A typical motif! White wants to harass the knight with h5 and make sure Black can't finish development by attacking the g7-pawn. }
12... Nxd3 13. cxd3 h5 { Preventing h5. } 14. Be3 Bd7 15. Rac1
{ Setting up the discovered attack and threatening Nxd5. } 15... Qa5 16. a3 Rc8
{ Black could play  16...Be7  to develop and prepare to castle. But we have the French pawn structure again with the bad bishop. We want to trade all the minor pieces except the bad bishop. After  17.Ne2  O-O  18.Bg5  also Nf4 is coming, and White has a winning position. }
17. Bg5 { Preventing ...Be7 and the bishop has no place to develop. } 17... d4
{ Black desperately wants to get some counterplay and gives up the pawn. } 18.
Nxd4 Qb6 19. Be3 Qd8
{ After  19...Qxb2  White has the brilliant  20.Nd5  when Black cannot capture with  20...exd5  since  21.e6  is a devastating blow. }
20. Ne4 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Qb8 22. Nf3 Bc6 23. Neg5 Bd5 24. Nd4
{ Threatening Ngxe6. } 24... Nxe5 25. Bf4
{ Pinning the knight and Black is in trouble. } 25... Bd6 26. Re1 Nf3+
{ The only way to avoid losing a piece. } 27. Ngxf3 Bxf4 28. Qxg7 Rf8 29. Ng5
{ Threatening Ngxe6 or Nfxe6! } 29... Bxg5 30. Qxg5 Kd7 31. Qxh5 Qf4 32. Qe5
{ Even in the endgame, Black's bishop would still be bad as it can't attack anything and is also not so helpful for stopping the h-pawn. }
32... Qg4 33. f3 Qg6 34. Rc1 Rc8 35. Rxc8 Kxc8 36. h5 Qh6 37. Ne2 f6 38. Qf4
{ White doesn't mind trading the h5-pawn for the f6-pawn. With two pawns up and a safe king, this is a technically winning position for White. }
38... Qxh5 39. Qxf6 e5 40. Ng3 Qe8 41. Nf5 Kb8 42. Qd6+
{ A fantastic victory from Dai! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3a) Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 "]
[Black "Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 6...fxe6 with 7...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory.  Our idea is straightforward. Either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or Black has to play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  , both allow us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Be4
{ Objectively the best reply and the move suggested by L'Ami in his Chessable course on the Caro-Kann. }
5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The third most popular move in the position. We immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop. We don't want to play the popular  6.h4  h5  7.e6  Qd6  when Black is threatening ...Qg3+ and White struggles to equalize. When Black ignores our pawn and attacks in the center with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p1P1b1/3p4/3P2P1/5P2/PPP4P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5  instead, we can play  7.h4  h5  8.Ne2  and aim for Nf4 to harass the bishop. }
6... fxe6 7. h4
{ Threatening h5, pushing the bishop back followed by f4 to completely lock in all Black's minor pieces on the kingside. In the game between GM Nepomniachtchi and GM Shankland  7...Nd7  was played, and White won after pushing back the bishop with  8.h5  .  After  8...Bf7  9.f4  we will transpose to this variation covered in the next chapter. Check out the model game here. }
7... c5 { Black ignores our threat and aims to break open the center! } 8. h5
{ Shutting down both bishops. } 8... Bf7 9. f4
{ This is strong for White as Black's pieces are cramped. We want to continue with Nf3-Ne5, and g5 is often a powerful idea, also shutting down Black's knight on the kingside. }
*

