[White "3a) Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 "]
[Black "Pawnstructure and plans 4...Be4 6...fxe6 with 7...h5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4 Be4
{ Objectively the best reply and the move suggested by L'Ami in his Chessable course on the Caro-Kann. }
5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The third most popular move in the position. We immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop. We don't want to play the popular  6.h4  h5  7.e6  Qd6  when Black is threatening ...Qg3+ and White struggles to equalize. When Black ignores our pawn and attacks in the center with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p1P1b1/3p4/3P2P1/5P2/PPP4P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5  instead, we can play  7.h4  h5  8.Ne2  and aim for Nf4 to harass the bishop. }
6... fxe6 7. h4
{ The structure is similar to the 4...Bg6 5...fxe6 structure, with the only difference being that our pawn is on f3 instead of f2. We plan to play h5 to restrict the dark-squared bishop. Black should reply with ...h5. }
7... h5
{ We already saw the variations with  7...Qc7  8.h5  and@@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2p1pp/2p1p1b1/3p4/3P2PP/5P2/PPP5/RNBQKBNR b KQkq h3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...c5  8.h5  when White gets the favorable pawn structure. Black should avoid that by playing @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2p1pp/2p1p1b1/3p4/3P2PP/5P2/PPP5/RNBQKBNR b KQkq h3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h5  after which Black is forced to enter the line  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  Qd6  10.Ne2  . }
8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qd6 10. Ne2
{ Let's summarize the main plans in this pawn structure. in this pawn structure. Black's bishop is stuck. Black should try to free themselves with ...e5 to eventually play ...e6 and free the bishop.  1@@EndBracket@@ If it was our move with White @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2p1p1/2pqp3/3p3p/3P2PP/3Q1P2/PPP1N3/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  11.Bf4  , we would reach a winning position immediately. The computer already gives +5, and after  11...Qb4+  12.Nd2  Black would only make things worse with  12...Qxb2  as after  13.Rb1  White has a massive lead in the development. By preventing the ...e5-break, we can bury the f8-bishop and play the rest of the game with a piece up. Of course, it's not White to move, and Black could directly play @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2p1p1/2pqp3/3p3p/3P2PP/3Q1P2/PPP1N3/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...e5  , which is covered from here.  2@@EndBracket@@ As we like lightning-fast development in variations where Black plays ...hxg4, we can often ignore that and continue development, this is an example: @@StartFEN@@r2k1b1r/pp1np1p1/2pqpnQ1/3p2Bp/3P2PP/5P2/PPPNN3/R3K2R b KQ - 8 13@@EndFEN@@  13...hxg4  14.O-O-O  going for rapid development as after  14...gxf3  15.Nxf3  White is already winning, as Black can't free the bishop. }
