[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory.  Our idea is straightforward. Either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or Black has to play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  , both allow us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Be4
{ Objectively the best reply and the move suggested by L'Ami in his Chessable course on the Caro-Kann. }
5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The third most popular move in the position. We immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop. We don't want to play the popular  6.h4  h5  7.e6  Qd6  when Black is threatening ...Qg3+ and White struggles to equalize. When Black ignores our pawn and attacks in the center with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p1P1b1/3p4/3P2P1/5P2/PPP4P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5  instead, we can play  7.h4  h5  8.Ne2  and aim for Nf4 to harass the bishop. }
6... fxe6 7. h4
{ Threatening h5, pushing the bishop back followed by f4 to completely lock in all Black's minor pieces on the kingside. In the game between GM Nepomniachtchi and GM Shankland  7...Nd7  was played, and White won after pushing back the bishop with  8.h5  .  After  8...Bf7  9.f4  we will transpose to this variation covered in the next chapter. Check out the model game here. }
7... h5 { The most critical reply, Black often goes wrong here already. } 8.
Bd3
{ Now that Black has weakened the light-squares with ...h5, it's the perfect time to exchange the bishops. }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qd6 { Black threatens ...Qg3+. } 10. Ne2
{ We develop and prevent ...Qg3+, also we get ready to develop with tempo with Bf4.  10.Qg6+  This was played in several games; however, after  10...Kd8  11.g5  e5  12.Qf7  e6  13.Qxb7  Qb4+  14.Qxb4  Bxb4+  the endgame is better for Black. }
10... e5
{ Black defends against Qg6+ and slowly wants to activate the bishop by moving both e-pawns forward. }
11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. Bf4
{ If Black knows what to do, the game will end in a perpetual; however, it is quite difficult for your opponent if they are not prepared.  When you feel like making a less committal decision and want to keep the game going, you can study the alternative variation with  12.Qg6+  here. I also considered  12.Bg5  when after  12...Qxb2  13.Qg6+  Kd8  14.Nf4  , the game should end in a perpetual check. In this line, it seems easier to defend for Black. }
12... Qe6
{ The critical move is  12...Qxb2  , but let's also see what happens when Black is too afraid to grab this pawn. }
13. Bxb8 { By trading, we prepare for Nf4 later! } 13... Rxb8 14. Nd2
{ We plan to play O-O-O, Rde1 and Nf4 } *

