[SetUp "1"]

{ How do we deal with the queen on b6? } 12. c3
{ Let's provoke Black to capture on b2. Also, we have the plan of Qb3 when Black shouldn't trade as it would activate our rook. }
12... Qxb2+ 13. Nd2 Qxc3 14. Rb1
{ White has a massive lead in development, and since Rxb7 is the threat, Black's position is falling apart. One cunning plan is to consolidate and trap the queen with Nb3, Kf2, and Bd2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 Tactics and Model Games "]
[Black "Exercise 4: Bayonet Attack 4...Be4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kbnr/pp2p1p1/2p5/3p3p/5BPP/3Q1P2/PqP1N3/RN2K2R w KQkq - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We are about to lose our rook! How will we get fantastic counterplay? } 13.
Nd4
{ We bring the knight in the attack! I showed this position to a couple of friends rated between 2200-2400 and asked them what to play with Black. None of them suggested  13...Na6  , which is the only good move for Black when we saw the variation here ending in perpetual check. And there was also the alternative variation for those who want to avoid the risk of perpetual check here. Most of my friends suggested playing  13...e5  when we win with  14.Qg6+  Kd8  15.Bxe5  Qc1+  16.Kf2  Qxh1  17.Ne6+  . }
13... Qxa1 14. O-O Qxd4+
{ This is the best move, meaning something went totally wrong for Black.  14...Nf6  loses after a very sharp variation  15.Nc3  Qb2  16.Rb1  Qa3  17.Qg6+  Kd8  18.Rxb7  , and here Black can try  18...Na6  19.Qf5  Qc5  20.Be5  , with the idea to eliminate the knight and give a mate. Black can still try the brilliant  20...Rb8  when we win with the even more brilliant  21.Ne4  . }
15. Qxd4 Nd7 { Black threatens ...e5 followed by ...Bc5! } 16. Re1
{ After  16...e5  17.Rxe5  White is doing great! Black's best move is  16...hxg4  when we can reply with  17.Qb4  putting pressure on the b7-pawn, when after  17...Nb6  18.fxg4  White keeps a significant advantage. }
*

