[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 Tactics and Model Games "]
[Black "Model Game: Nepomniachtchi-Shankland 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between GM Ian Nepomniachtchi and Samuel Shankland in Khanty-Mansiysk, Russia, in 2017. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 Be4 5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The two time Candidates winner goes for our recommendation. While this move is certainly well-represented in the databases, it was never seen in grandmaster play before 2017. }
6... fxe6 7. h4 Nd7 8. h5 { Ian follows the plan to push back the bishop. }
8... Bf7 9. f4
{ Getting ready to play Nf3 and gaining more space. We transpose to the variation that will be covered in the next chapter after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq g3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg6  5.e6  fxe6  6.h4  Nd7  7.h5  Bf7  8.f4  . }
9... e5
{ An excellent practical decision. The e6 pawn is unlikely to survive in the long term, so Black decides to unload it immediately to work on his development. }
10. fxe5 e6 11. Nf3
{ 11.Nd2  is a minor improvement over the game I recommended in the course. We go to the f3-square with our queenside knight and leave the e2-square open for the kingside knight to give maximum support to the center. The theory has been covered in the course here. }
11... c5 12. c3 Ne7 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. O-O Qb6 15. Kg2
{ Safeguarding the pawn as after  15...cxd4  16.cxd4  Nxd4  17.Nxd4  Qxd4  18.Rxf7  Kxf7  19.Bg6+  wins. }
15... Rc8 16. a3
{ A significant mistake ignoring the threat of ...cxd4 after  16...cxd4  17.cxd4  Nxd4  18.Nxd4  Qxd4  19.Rxf7?  doesn't work anymore as it runs into  19...Rxc1  and Black wins the game.   @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/pp1n1bpp/1qn1p3/2ppP2P/3P2P1/2PB1N2/PP4K1/RNBQ1R2 w k - 7 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Na3  would have prevented this after  16...cxd4  17.cxd4  Nxd4  18.Nxd4  Qxd4  19.Rxf7  Rxc1  , the rook is defending, and we play  20.Rxc1  keeping the discovered attack after  20...Kxf7  21.Bg6+  Black could still play  19...Bxa3  , though, and White is much better. The computer suggests that @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/pp1n1bpp/4p3/3pP2P/3q2P1/N2B4/PP4K1/R1BQ1R2 w k - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Bg6  would be even stronger for White and we win after  19...Qxd1  20.Bxf7+  Ke7  21.Bg5+  . }
16... cxd4
{ After  17.cxd4  Nxd4  18.Nxd4  Qxd4  19.Rxf7?  runs into  19...Rxc1  and Black wins the game. }
17. cxd4 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Qxd4 19. Bg6
{ The best move since  19.Rxf7  runs into  19...Rxc1  . } 19... Qxd1 20. Bxf7+
Kd8
{ With  20...Ke7  Black could try to keep attacking the bishop. This would run into  21.Bg5+  when after  21...Nf6  22.Rxd1  Kxf7  23.exf6  gxf6  White keeps a significant advantage. }
21. Rxd1 Ke7 22. Rf1 Rc2+ 23. Kh1 Nxe5 24. Bg5+ Kd7 25. Nc3
{ Black must now prevent Rae1. } 25... Nxg4 { Aiming for ...Rh2+. } 26. Bxe6+
{ A brilliant tactic. } 26... Kxe6 27. Rae1+ Kd6
{ Black play  27...Kd6  allowing a tactic with  28.Rxf8  with the idea of  28...Rxf8  29.Be7+  .  Black doesn't have a good alternative since after @@StartFEN@@5b1r/pp4pp/4k3/3p2BP/6n1/P1N5/1Pr5/4RR1K b - - 1 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Kd7  28.Rf7+  Kc6  29.Re6+  Kc5  30.Rc7+  Kd4  31.Ne2+  Kd3  32.Nf4+  wins the rook. And @@StartFEN@@5b1r/pp4pp/4k3/3p2BP/6n1/P1N5/1Pr5/4RR1K b - - 1 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Ne5  28.Bf4  Bd6  29.Nb5  threatens both Nxd6 as well as Nd4+. }
28. Rxf8
{ After  28...Rxf8  29.Be7+  Kd7  30.Bxf8  Nf2+  31.Kh2  Black still has  31...d4  , which forces the endgame after  32.Re2  Rxe2  33.Nxe2  d3  34.Nc3  d2  35.Bxg7  d1=Q  36.Nxd1  Nxd1  , where Black still has to fight for a draw. }
28... Nf2+ { A miscalculation. } 29. Rxf2 Rxf2 30. Nb5+ Kc6 31. Nxa7+ Kc7 32.
Nb5+ Kb8 33. b4 Rf5 34. Be7 Rxh5+ 35. Kg2 d4 36. Nxd4 Rd5 37. Bc5 Rhd8 38. Re4
h5 39. a4 g5 40. a5 g4 41. a6 bxa6 42. Nc6+ Kc7 43. Nxd8 Kxd8 44. Kg3 Rf5 45.
Kh4 Rd5 46. Re3 Kc7 47. Re7+ Kb8 48. Bb6 Rb5 49. Bc7+ Ka8 50. Ba5 Rf5 51. Re6
Kb7 52. Rg6 Ka7 53. Rb6 Rd5 54. Rf6 Kb7 55. Rf4 Ka7 56. Kg3 Rd3+ 57. Kf2 Rd5
58. Ke3 Re5+ 59. Kf2 Kb7 60. Rf7+ Ka8
{ Black should play  60...Kc6  to avoid getting cut off on the back rank. Now White has the plan to bring the bishop to c5. }
61. Rg7 Re4 62. Kg3 Re5 63. Kf4 Rd5 64. Ke4 Rb5 65. Kd4 Rf5 66. Bb6 Rb5 67.
Rg8+
{ A classy move! Before shutting down the rook with Bc5, Ian also prevents the rook from coming back into the game with ...Rb7. }
67... Kb7 68. Bc5 Kc7 69. Ke4
{ With the rook out of play Black is helpless, and Shankland resigned the game. A great victory from Nepomniachtichi. }
