[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 Tactics and Model Games "]
[Black "Model Game: Grandelius-Kremer 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between GM Nils Grandelius and GM Vincent Keymer in Riga, Latvia, 2021. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 Be4 5. f3 Bg6 6. e6 Qd6 7. exf7+ Bxf7 8. Nc3
Nd7 9. f4 e6 10. Nf3 Qc7 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. Ng5
{ We covered the theory until here in the course.  12...Bxf4  doesn't work because of  13.Nxf7  Kxf7  14.Bxf4  Qxf4  15.Rf1!  @@StartFEN@@r3k1nr/ppqn1bpp/2pbp3/3p4/3P1PP1/2NB1N2/PPP4P/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne5  is a possible alternative. }
12... h5 13. Bd2 Nf8
{ A creative idea. The knight was not doing much, and Black wants to find extra support for the weak e6-pawn. }
14. Rf1 hxg4
{ Black captured at the perfect moment.  14...O-O-O  15.Nxf7  Qxf7  16.g5  would be great for White as we take away the f6-square for the knight. We don't have to be afraid of  16...Ne7  17.Qf3  Nf5  as after  18.Ne2  , the knight, is not doing much on f5. }
15. Qxg4 Bh5 16. Qg2 Ne7 17. Ne2 Qd7
{ Preparing to either castle queenside or kick away the annoying bishop with Ng3. }
18. Ng3 Bg6 19. Bxg6+ Nexg6 20. O-O-O
{ The position is great for White! Black still has the backward e6-pawn, and the knight on f8 is passive. White wants to play f5 and break open the position to have juicy forks with Nf7. Black's best defense would be  20...Nh4  21.Qh3  g6  preventing the f5-break. }
20... O-O-O 21. f5
{ White goes for the pawn break and gets a dominating position. } 21... Nh4
{ After  21...exf5  22.Nxf5  White will win at least an exchange with the fork on f7. }
22. Qh3
{ Pinning the knight. White is winning, and Grandlius converted the position well. }
22... e5 23. dxe5 Bxe5 24. Ne6 Nxf5 25. Qxh8 Nxe6 26. Qh3 Nxg3 27. hxg3 Nc5 28.
Qxd7+ Rxd7 29. Be3 b6 30. g4 Ne4 31. Rf5 Re7 32. Rdf1 Kd7 33. Rf7 Bf6 34. Rxe7+
Bxe7 35. Rf7 g5 36. Kd1 c5 37. Ke2 b5 38. Rg7 b4 39. Rg8 a5 40. Ra8 Bd8 41. Ra6
