[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) Bayonet Attack 4...Bg6"]
[Black "Bayonet Attack 4...Bg6 with 5...fxe6 #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or Black has to play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  , which both allow us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Bg6 5. e6 { We immediately want to shut down the dark-squared bishop. }
5... fxe6 6. h4
{ In a Titled Tuesday match, GM Mamedyarov won a smooth game as his opponent already went wrong here by playing  7...Bf7  . }
6... Nd7 { The best development move for Black, however, they allow h5. } 7. h5
{ We don't hesitate to kick the bishop back. } 7... Bf7 8. f4
{ We play against the ...e5-break and aim to lock up Black's minor pieces on the kingside. A typical motif is g5 to prevent the g8-knight from developing. This same position could also arise from the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq g3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  6.e6  fxe6  7.h4  Nd7  8.h5  Bf7  9.f4  move order. }
8... Ngf6
{ In the model game Nepomniachtchi-Shankland, Black chose the immediate @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npbpp/2p1p3/3p3P/3P1PP1/8/PPP5/RNBQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5  when after  9.fxe5  e6  , a suggested improvement over the game would be  10.Nd2  when we can go for Ndf3 and leave the e2-square open for the other knight to give maximum support to the center.  An interesting alternative is @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npbpp/2p1p3/3p3P/3P1PP1/8/PPP5/RNBQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nh6  when we can also play  9.Nc3  with the idea that after  9...Qb6  10.g5  Nf5  11.Nce2  covers both the center and defends against ...Ng3. We can stabilize the position with Nf3 and c3 when Black's bishops remain stuck.  The computer also suggests @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1npbpp/2p1p3/3p3P/3P1PP1/8/PPP5/RNBQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...g5  when after  9.fxg5  Black wants to break free with  9...e5  .  We reply with the cunning  10.g6  with the idea that  10...hxg6  runs into  11.hxg6  Rxh1  12.gxf7+  Kxf7  13.Qf3+  winning the rook back. So Black should play  10...Be6  when after  11.gxh7  Rxh7  12.g5  restricts the knight on the kingside. What a spectacular position that is! }
9. Nc3
{ We will kick the knight with g5 next move, and Black doesn't have the e4-square anymore. When Black pins us with  9...Qa5  we can unpin with  10.Bd2  and continue with g5 the next move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) Bayonet Attack 4...Bg6"]
[Black "Pawn structure differences 4...Be4 6...fxe6 and 4...Bg6 5...fxe6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 Bg6 5. e6 fxe6 6. h4 h5
{ Many other moves have been tried, but when Black allows us to play h5, the position is perfect for us. }
7. Bd3 { We dominate the light squares. } 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3
{ The position is exactly the same as the position we saw after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq g3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  6.e6  fxe6  7.h4  h5  8.Bd3  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  with the only difference that the pawn is f2 instead of f3. This makes a massive difference in how the game continues. Let's summarize the differences.  1@@EndBracket@@ With the pawn on f3, Black should play  9...Qd6  threatening ...Qg3+ If Black would instead play @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2p1p1/2p1p3/3p3p/3P2PP/3Q1P2/PPP5/RNB1K1NR b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...hxg4  then this runs into  10.Qg6+  Kd7  11.fxg4  with a significant advantage for White.  2@@EndBracket@@ With the pawn on f2 the same reply with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2p1p1/2p1p3/3p3p/3P2PP/3Q4/PPP2P2/RNB1K1NR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qd6  would be losing for Black after  9.Qg6+  Kd8  White still has the f3-square available for the knight, and we play  10.Nf3  going for the royal fork with Ne5-Nf7+. }
8... hxg4 9. Qg6+ { We give the check and grab back the pawn. } 9... Kd7 10.
Qxg4 Nf6 11. Qh3
{ Keeping the pin on the e6-pawn. So Black is more or less forced to enter this position when we have the powerful plan Nf3-Ne5+. Therefore Black should continue as in the variation here. }
