[White "5a) Bayonet Attack 4...Bd7"]
[Black "Pawn structure 4...Bd7 with 5...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 Bd7 5. Nc3 e6 6. Be3
{ Here, we see another structure with the Bad French Bishop. A big difference is that here our pawn is on g4. Compared to the other Bad French bishop structure, losing the e5-pawn can be more problematic since the g4-pawn, and f3-square can be weak. Let's summarize the plans in this structure.  1@@EndBracket@@ We want to prevent the ...c5-break. This is shown in variations after  6...Qb6  7.Na4  Qa5+  8.c3  , where we improved our position because it's more difficult for Black to go for the ...c5-break. And after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/2p1p3/3pP3/3P2P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6  , we also play  7.Na4  to prevent the c5-break.  2@@EndBracket@@ To ...h5, we will always respond with ...gxh5 and grab the pawn up. This differs from the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg6  positions where the bishop can recapture on h5.  3@@EndBracket@@ Keep in mind that from the Black point of view, they have no choice but to break open sooner or later with either ...c5 or ...h5 since they lack space. }
*

