{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or Black has to play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  , which both allow us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Bd7
{ The third most popular move and a critical one. The problem for Black is when they play ...e6, they accept to have a bad 'French bishop' locked in within the pawn chain. Having the pawn on g4 benefits us since Black cannot use the f5-square for the knight or bishop. Nevertheless, having the pawn on g4 could be a significant drawback in case the position opens up, as the pawn can be weak, and also, the squares on the kingside are weakened. Therefore our strategy is to prevent Black's break with ...c5 and keep the position closed. }
5. Nc3
{ I also considered  5.c4  , but we are overextended with White, and Black is doing fine after  5...e6  6.Nc3  c5  when the position opens up and our g4-pawn becomes weak.  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2p5/3pP3/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Be3  would almost be the same as we transpose after  5...e6  6.Nc3  .   I chose to recommend @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2p5/3pP3/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  , as in the variation with  5...h5  , we can benefit from delaying the bishop's development after  6.gxh5  Bf5  7.Nge2  Bg4  when  8.Bg5  pins the e7-pawn. }
5... e6 6. Be3
{ The plan is prophylactic; we play against the ...c5-break, which Black inevitably should play at some point. }
6... Ne7
{ Black wants to play for ...h5 and play ...Nf5. We prefer to keep our pawn on f2 defending the bishop when Black goes for the ...h5 and ...Nf5 plan. }
7. Nf3 h5 8. gxh5 Nf5 9. Bg5
{ 9.Bd3  is an alternative when after  9...Nxe3  10.fxe3  c5  White keeps an advantage.   It seems to me that this position is more difficult to play then my recommendation  9.Bg5  since after  9...Be7  10.h4  c5  11.dxc5  Nc6  12.Bd3  White has a fantastic position and plans to go Nb5-Nd6+. }
9... Qb6 10. Na4 { Same idea that Na4 helps us as we prevent the ...c5 break. }
10... Qc7 11. h4
{ It's useful to protect the bishop. The logical developing move  11.Bd3  was played in the top GM game between Van Foreest and Harikrishna. This is a big mistake as Black has  11...Nxd4  12.Nxd4  c5  attacking both the knights and after  13.Nb5  Qxe5+  14.Be3  c4  Black wins back the piece. This was missed by Harikrishna, after which Van Foreest won the game.  This variation shows why it's useful to play the recommended @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/ppqb1pp1/2p1p3/3pPnBP/N2P4/5N2/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11.h4  to defend the bishop, and White is now ready to play Bd3 next move. }
