{ This game was played by GM Jorden van Foreest  (2701)  and GM Pentala Harikrishna  (2730)  in an online rapid team championship in 2021. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 Bd7 5. Nc3 e6 6. Be3 Ne7 7. Nf3 h5 8. gxh5
Nf5 9. Bg5 Qb6 10. Na4 Qc7 11. Bd3
{ As explained here, we will play  11.h4  instead. It's useful to protect the bishop. The logical developing move  11.Bd3  was played by Van Foreest here is a big mistake, as Black has  11...Nxd4  12.Nxd4  c5  attacking both the knights, and after  13.Nb5  Qxe5+  14.Be3  c4  Black regains the piece with a better position. This shows why it's useful to play the recommended @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/ppqb1pp1/2p1p3/3pPnBP/N2P4/5N2/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11.h4  to defend the bishop, and White is now ready to play Bd3 next move. }
11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxe5+
{ A significant mistake  12...c5  would have given Black a slight advantage as  13.Nb5  doesn't work because Black has  13...Qxe5+  14.Be3  c4  and Black will regain the piece with a better position. }
13. Be3 c5 14. Nf3 Qxh5
{ 14.Qc7  would have been much stronger. When Black holds on to the c5-pawn, the knight on a4 is misplaced. }
15. Nxc5 d4 { Double attack on the knight and bishop. } 16. Nxd7 dxe3 17. Nxf8
exf2+ 18. Kxf2 Kxf8
{ After all the trades, Jorden remains a piece up and wins the game smoothly. }
19. Be4 Qc5+ 20. Qd4 Nd7 21. Rad1 Rb8 22. b4 Qxd4+ 23. Rxd4 Nf6 24. Rhd1 Ke7
