[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Punishing  Club Player Mistakes  "]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6 queen sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]

{ In these two chapters for club players, we will discuss how to punish the frequent mistakes at the 1600-level. If you are at an advanced level and are rated over 2000, I recommend skipping these chapters, as your opponents are unlikely to make these mistakes. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3
{ We develop and protect the pawn!  4.dxc5  is more popular and a good alternative. The disadvantage is that Black can play  4...e6  5.Be3  Nd7  Threatening to win back the pawn. We can pin the knight with  6.Bb5  , however, after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5, targetting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nc6
{ Black develops and puts more pressure on the center. Now that Black played ...Nc6, they cannot play ...Nd7 anymore to regain the c5-pawn. That's why we capture on c5 now. }
5. dxc5 Bg4
{ As Black plays the Caro-Kann, they want to develop their light-squared bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
6. c3
{ A multi-purpose move, it gives us the option to stabilize our dark-squared bishop on the d4-square to hold on to the c5 and e5-pawns, but also allows us to safeguard our c5-pawn with b4. Furthermore, the open diagonal for the queen can come in handy as it allows Qb3 or Qa4. We also set up a sneaky trap for our opponent. }
6... Nxe5
{ This queen sacrifice was in the clickable lines already in the course, but it's good to train it so that you won't forget about this beautiful queen sacrifice. In my attacking repertoire for Club Players:  1.e4  , we saw this sacrifice three times.  6...Nxe5  was the second most popular move at the Club Player level, played in about 30% of the games. }
7. Nxe5 { A powerful tactic, seemingly sacrificing the queen. } 7... Bxd1 8.
Bb5+ { With this deadly check, we will regain the queen. } 8... Qd7 9. Bxd7+
{ We will be two pieces up with a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Punishing  Club Player Mistakes  "]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell 4...Nc6 piece blunder"]
[Result "*"]

{ In these two chapters for club players, we will discuss how to punish the frequent mistakes at the 1600-level. If you are at an advanced level and are rated over 2000, I recommend skipping these chapters, as your opponents are unlikely to make these mistakes. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3
{ We develop and protect the pawn!  4.dxc5  is more popular and a good alternative. The disadvantage is that Black can play  4...e6  5.Be3  Nd7  Threatening to win back the pawn. We can pin the knight with  6.Bb5  , however, after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5, targetting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nc6
{ Black develops and puts more pressure on the center. Now that Black played ...Nc6, they cannot play ...Nd7 anymore to regain the c5-pawn. That's why we capture on c5 now. }
5. dxc5 Bg4
{ As Black plays the Caro-Kann, they want to develop their light-squared bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
6. c3
{ A multi-purpose move, it gives us the option to stabilize our dark-squared bishop on the d4-square to hold on to the c5 and e5-pawns, but also allows us to safeguard our c5-pawn with b4. Furthermore, the open diagonal for the queen can come in handy as it allows Qb3 or Qa4. We also set up a sneaky trap for our opponent. }
6... e6 7. Be3 Nxe5
{ And now  7...Nxe5  is again a big blunder, and this time the most popular move at the 1600-level. }
8. Qa4+
{ A cunning move, We are unpinning the knight and attacking the king, knight, and bishop. }
8... Qd7 { Black counterattacks with the queen. } 9. Bb5
{ Pinning the queen. The trade with  9.Qxd7+  is not good because Black can save the knight with  9...Nxd7  . }
9... Nc6 10. Qxg4 { We are winning the bishop. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) Punishing  Club Player Mistakes  "]
[Black "Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 6...h6 mistake#1"]
[Result "*"]

{ In these two chapters for club players, we will discuss how to punish the frequent mistakes at the 1600-level. If you are at an advanced level and are rated over 2000, I recommend skipping these chapters, as your opponents are unlikely to make these mistakes. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain. Or Black has to play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  , which both allow us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Be4
{ Objecitely the best reply and the move suggested by L'Ami in his Chessable course on the Caro-Kann. }
5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The third most popular move in the position. We immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop. We don't want to play the popular  6.h4  h5  7.e6  Qd6  when Black is threatening ...Qg3+ and White struggles to equalize. }
6... fxe6 7. h4 { Threatening h5, pushing the bishop back. } 7... h6
{ This is the most popular move at the Club Player level, Black creates an escape square for the bishop on h7. It's a big mistake, as it weakens the light squares around the king. When Black allows us h5 to kick the bishop, we will always play that. }
8. h5
{ We always play h5 when Black allows us to do so and kick the bishop back. }
8... Bh7 9. Bd3
{ Now it's time to exchange Black's Caro-Kann bishop and dominate the light squares. }
9... Bxd3
{ A frequent mistake for Black is to capture the bishop. Typically in other Caro-Kann positions, this is what Black should play, but now their light squares are weakened too much. }
10. Qxd3
{ We are dominating the light squares. A dream position for our knight would be the square on e5, where we have tactical mating and forking possibilities and are also on a central outpost where no opponent pawns can chase us away. }
10... Nd7 11. Qg6# { Finishes the game with a smothered mate. } *

