[White "6b) Club Player Tactics and Model Games "]
[Black "Model Game: Podolsky-Moliboga"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between Anton Podolsky  (2289)  and Vladimir Moliboga  (2271)  in Lviv, Ukraine, in 2010. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 Bg6 5. h4
{ Note that a different move order is used in the course. We will start with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p3b1/3pP3/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e6  , and after  5...fxe6  6.h4  h6  7.h5  Bh7  , we transpose to the variation in the game here. The move order in the game allows Black a powerful extra option after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p3b1/3pP3/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h4  h5  when after  6.e6  they can play  6...hxg4  . }
5... h6 6. h5 Bh7 7. e6 fxe6 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nf6 10. Nf3 Ne4 11. Nbd2 Qa5
12. O-O { So far, everything is covered here in the course. } 12... Nd7
{ Black allows White to win the e4-pawn since  12...Nxd2  13.Bxd2  Qb6  14.Qg6+  Kd8  15.Ne5  would lose even more material when White threatens Nf7, forking the king and rook. }
13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Qxe4 Qd5
{ An important moment in the game. White definitely doesn't want to trade queens as they have a much safer king and  15.Qxd5  exd5  would also improve Black's pawn structure. }
15. Qg6+ Kd8 16. Ne5
{ A cunning move, which forever locks in Black's dark-squared bishop now that the e-pawns and g-pawn can't move forward. White forces a trade by threatening the fork with Nf7+, which blows open the position in front of Black's king. }
16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. Be3 Qf6 19. Rad1+ Kc7 20. Qd3
{ Mate will follow soon as Black's dark-squared bishop and rook keep on being stuck in the corner. }
20... Rc8 21. Bxa7
{ Creating an unstoppable threat of Qd7#. Shockingly, a 2271-rated player got destroyed so easily. This game shows the power of the prophylactic pawn sacrifice @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p3b1/3pP3/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e6  covered from here in the course, after which the bishop never participated again. Usually, it won't be so easy to defeat an advanced player like this. Still, surely we can win against club players with this strategy. The variation with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq g3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg6  5.e6  fxe6  6.h4  h6  it's the most popular way to reply to the Shirov attack at the Club Player level. After  7.h5  , we already have a significant advantage dominating the light-squared, and we have the potential for quick checkmates and forks. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Extensive Course Summary "]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6  with 7...Bxf3 "]
[Result "*"]

{ The Extensive Course Summary repeats the most important variations in the course. These are the moves you are most likely to face, and it includes the full version of the variations in the Quickstarter Guide and a couple of other essential variations. }
1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5 4. Nf3
{ We develop and protect the pawn!  4.dxc5  is more popular and a good alternative. The disadvantage is that Black can play  4...e6  5.Be3  Nd7  Threatening to win back the pawn. We can pin the knight with  6.Bb5  , however, after  6...Ne7  Black is ready to play ...Nf5, targetting the bishop, and Black has compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nc6
{ Black develops and puts more pressure on the center. Now that Black played ...Nc6, they cannot play ...Nd7 anymore to regain the c5-pawn. That's why we capture on c5 now. }
5. dxc5 Bg4
{ As Black plays the Caro-Kann, they want to develop their light-squared bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
6. c3
{ Preparing to safeguard our c5-pawn with b4. We also set up a juicy trick as  6...Nxe5  immediately loses after  7.Nxe5  Bxd1  8.Bb5+  . }
6... e6 7. Be3
{ Again  7...Nxe5  doesn't work since  8.Qa4+  Qd7  9.Bb5  wins the game. }
7... Bxf3
{ The most popular move. It's bad for Black to give up on the light-squared bishop so easily. }
8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ { Developing with a check! } 9... Nc6 10. c4
{ Increasing the pressure on the center. White is already doing great. } 10...
Nf6 11. Nc3
{ White increases the pressure on the center and has a winning position already. After  11...a6  12.Ba4  Be7  13.cxd5  exd5  14.O-O  O-O  15.Rad1  White wins the d5-pawn. Check out how GM Antipov outplayed IM Usmanov in a flawless game. }
11... Be7 12. cxd5 { By trading the pawns we give Black an isolated d5-pawn. }
12... exd5
{ If Black instead plays  12...Nxd5  , we can immediately pin the knight with  13.O-O-O  and  13...Qa5  doesn't scare us as we chase away the queen with  14.Bd2  and can reply to  14...Nxc3  with  15.Bxc6+  .  So Black should instead play  14...Qc7  when after  15.Nxd5  exd5  16.Bc3  We win the g7 or d5-pawn with a winning position. }
13. O-O O-O 14. Rfd1 Qa5 15. a3
{ An important move! We prepare b4, which chases away the queen and allows our knight to play Nxd5. Also, b4 safeguards the c5-pawn. We have the bishop pair and will win the d5-pawn, our position is winning. }
