[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Extensive Course Summary "]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6 with 7...Nge7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 Nge7
{ Black plans to play ...Nf5-Nxe3, we don't have to be worried about that as we can reply to ...Nf5 with Bd4. }
8. Nbd2 { Watch how GM Inarkiev won versus WGM Fuchs in this model game. } 8...
Nf5 9. Bd4
{ We prevent ...Nxe3 and hold on to the c5-pawn.  9...Nfxd4  10.cxd4  Nxd4  loses a piece after  11.Qa4+  . }
9... Be7 10. Bb5
{ In this pawn structure, it's best to use our bishop to eliminate the knight to get rid of one of the attackers on e5. Ideas with  10.h3  , doesn't force Black to trade their bishop since after  10...Bh5  11.g4  , they can still play  11...Nfxd4  to avoid losing a piece. }
10... O-O 11. Bxc6
{ We like to trade the knight to release the pressure against our center. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O
{ White is a clean pawn up! Black would like to pressure the c5-pawn with ...a5, ...Qc7-Qa7. With White, we want to stabilize with b3, avoiding counterplay against the b2-pawn. And when Black targets the c5-pawn, we want to be ready to play h3-g4 and force Black to trade on d4 so that we maintain a pawn up.  A sample line is  12...a5  13.b3  Qc7  14.h3  Bh5  15.Re1  Qa7  16.g4  Nxd4  17.cxd4  With the trade, we secured the c5-pawn and stay a healthy pawn up. Black's bishop pair does not compensate for the pawn since Black's dark-squared bishop is passive. }
