[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Extensive Course Summary "]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6 with 7...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 a6
{ Black wants to stop Bb5 permanently. } 8. Qb3
{ We go directly for the b7-pawn. } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxb7
{ With a double attack on the knight and bishop! } 9... Na5
{ This move looks obvious for Black as they win a piece. It's a mistake, as White has more than enough compensation. }
10. Qb4
{ Brilliant! White will regain the piece after  10...Bh5  11.Qa4+  Ke7  12.Qh4+  we fork the king and the bishop. After  10...Be4  11.Qa4+  Ke7  12.Nd2  White will play b4 next, and Black's position is falling apart. }
10... d4 { Black's only move. } 11. gxf3 dxe3 12. Qa4+
{ We give a powerful intermediate check to misplace Black's king. } 12... Ke7
13. fxe3
{ White has more than enough compensation for the piece. Black's king and pieces on the kingside are misplaced. }
13... Qc7
{ Black wants to play ...Qxc5 followed by ...Qxe3+ and ...Qxe5 where they win three pawns and defend the knight again. We should prevent this and defend the e5-pawn. }
14. f4 Qxc5 15. Nd2
{ A fantastic move allowing  15...Qxe3+  since after  16.Be2  , the knight on a5 is hanging. }
15... Qxe3+ 16. Be2 Rd8 { Black goes for counterplay and threatens ...Qxd2+. }
17. Nf3 Qb6 18. Nd4
{ We threaten Qxa5+ winning the knight, when after ...Qxa5+ Nxc6+ wins the queen. White has a winning position. }
