[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...Nc6 with 7...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. dxc5 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Be3 a6
{ Black wants to stop Bb5 permanently. } 8. Qb3
{ We go directly for the b7-pawn. } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxb7
{ With a double attack on the knight and bishop! } 9... Nge7
{ The most critical move which has been played only ones. } 10. gxf3 Ra7 11.
Qb6 { Keeping an eye on the rook to prevent Black from playing ...Nxe5  . }
11... Qa8 { By protecting the knight, Black prepares ...Nf5-Nxe3. } 12. Nd2
{ We want to get the knight to b3 to support the c5-pawn. } 12... Nf5
{ Another option for Black is  12...Nxe5  , after which we play  13.Qa5  .  Whenever Black gets ready to castle and plays ...Be7, we will go for Qa4+. The variation could continue with  13...Nf5  14.O-O-O  Be7  15.Qa4+  . }
13. Nb3 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Be7 15. Nd4
{ We force Black to capture on e5 but, in return, gain control of the c6-square!  15...Bh4?  16.Kd2  would greatly improve our position as the bishop is no longer attacking the c5-pawn. }
15... Nxe5 16. f4 Nd7 17. Qc6
{ As our king is weaker, we force the trade of queens. Black can hold the balance with  17...Bxc5  18.Qxa8  when we reach an equal endgame. }
