[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Extensive Course Summary "]
[Black "Khenkin-Arkell variation 4...cxd4 6...e6 with 7...Nb4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... c5 4. Nf3 cxd4
{ The second most popular move. Black wants to avoid the position after  4...Nc6  5.dxc5  , where Black had a though time regaining the pawn. }
5. Qxd4
{ A fascinating move played by Aronian, MVL, Grischuk, and many other top grandmasters. The idea is that our queen is perfectly placed on f4, where it defends the e5-pawn and can put pressure on the kingside. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ Black locks in the light-squared bishop in the pawn chain. Usually, the typical Caro-Kann idea is to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6. When the bishop is inside the pawn chain, Black has a bad French bishop. This makes our light-squared bishop extremely dangerous on d3, where it's eyeing at the h7-pawn. Black cannot safely castle. This position can also be reached from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3pP3/3Q4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.Qf4  move order. }
7. Nc3 Nb4
{ The main move, also recommended by L'Ami in his Caro-Kann course. } 8. Qd2
{ A novelty, this position was reached by five GMs, who all played  8.Bd3  .  Even though nothing is wrong with that, we prefer not to exchange the powerful light-squared bishop.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nb4  We will play the novelty  8.Qd2  keeping the bishop alive and after the slow  7...Nge7  or  7...h6  or  7...a6  go for  8.Bd3  .   The logic behind this is as follows: When Black plays a slow move like @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  we will play  8.Bd3  and allow  8...Nb4  , since we can prevent our opponent from castling and gain a significant advantage after  9.Ne2  Nxd3+  10.cxd3  Ne7  11.Bd2  Ng6  12.Qg3  Be7  13.h4  h5  14.Nf4  , all these moves are explained in much more detail here.   In the variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3pP3/5Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nb4  , the same ideas wouldn't have worked after  8.Bd3  Nxd3+  9.cxd3  Ne7  As we didn't castle yet @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/4p3/3pP3/5Q2/2NP1N2/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne2  Ng6  11.Qg3  wouldn't work well as Black has counterplay with either  11...Qa5+  or  11...Bb4+  and also after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/4p3/3pP3/5Q2/2NP1N2/PP3PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  Ng6  11.Qg3  Be7  , we are too late with playing  12.h4  because of  12...Bxh4  . }
8... a6
{ Also suggested by L'Ami Lifetime Caro-Kann repertoire to prevent Bb5+. } 9.
a3
{ We will kick the knight back and get ready to play Bd3 and develop the powerful bishop. }
9... Nc6 10. Bd3
{ With our bishop on d3, it's dangerous for Black to castle kingside. They should bring the knight to g6 to break the bishop's diagonal. }
10... Nge7 { Black plans to play ... Ng6 putting pressure on the e5-pawn. } 11.
O-O Ng6 12. Bxg6
{ This may be counter-intuitive looking at our previous play to go @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/1n3Q2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd2  and not trade the light-squared bishop. The trade damages Black's pawn structure, though, as we are preventing the ...f6 break. This move has not been covered by L'Ami in his Caro-Kann lifetime repertoire course. }
12... hxg6 13. Re1
{ This structure is uncomfortable for Black as they can't go for a break with ...f6 anymore. Black has a weak 'French bishop' locked in within the pawn chain. We have a positional strategy here. We want to trade all the other minor pieces and leave Black with the weak French light-squared bishop. Another typical plan is to stabilize the position with a knight on the d4-square, where it can't be attacked by pawns and blocks the a7-g1 diagonal. A variation where everything goes according to the plan would be  13...Be7  14.Qd3  O-O  15.Ne2  Bd7  16.c3  Rc8  17.Ned4  Qb6  18.Nxc6  Bxc6  19.Bg5  Bc5  20.Qd2  Rfe8  21.Be3  , we would have a positionally winning position here. White has an extra knight into the attack as Black's light-squared bishop is locked in behind the pawn chain. }
