[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Extensive Course Summary "]
[Black "Bayonet Attack 4...Be4 6...fxe6 7...h5 10...e5 with 12.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  .  The latter allows us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Be4
{ Objectively, the best reply and the move suggested by L'Ami in his Chessable course on the Caro-Kann. }
5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The third most popular move in the position. We immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop. We don't want to play the popular  6.h4  h5  7.e6  Qd6  when Black is threatening ...Qg3+ and White struggles to equalize. }
6... fxe6 7. h4
{ Threatening h5, pushing the bishop back followed by f4 to completely lock in all Black's minor pieces on the kingside. In the game between GM Nepomniachtchi and GM Shankland  7...Nd7  was played, and White won after pushing back the bishop with  8.h5  .  Check out this model game here. }
7... h5 { The most critical reply, Black often goes wrong here already. } 8.
Bd3
{ Now that Black has weakened the light-squares with ...h5, it's the perfect time to exchange the bishops. }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qd6 { Black threatens ...Qg3+. } 10. Ne2
{ We develop and prevent ...Qg3+, also we get ready to develop with tempo with Bf4.  10.Qg6+  was played in several games; however, after  10...Kd8  11.g5  e5  12.Qf7  e6  13.Qxb7  Qb4+  14.Qxb4  Bxb4+  The endgame is better for Black. }
10... e5
{ Black defends against Qg6+ and slowly wants to activate the bishop by moving both e-pawns forward. }
11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. Bf4
{ If Black knows what to do, the game will end in a perpetual; however, it is quite difficult for your opponent if they are not prepared. When you feel like making a less commital decision and want to keep the game going, you can study the alternative variation with  12.Qg6+  here. I also considered  12.Bg5  when after  12...Qxb2  13.Qg6+  Kd8  14.Nf4  , the game should end in a perpetual check. In this line, it seems easier to defend for Black. }
12... Qxb2 13. Nd4
{ We bring the knight in the attack! I showed this position to a couple of friends rated between 2200-2400 and asked them what to play with Black. None of them suggested ...Na6 they often wanted to play  13...e5  when we win with  14.Qg6+  Kd8  15.Bxe5  Qc1+  16.Kf2  Qxh1  17.Ne6+  . }
13... Qxa1 14. O-O Qxd4+
{ This is the best move, meaning something went totally wrong for Black.  14...Nf6  loses after a very sharp variation  15.Nc3  Qb2  16.Rb1  Qa3  17.Qg6+  Kd8  18.Rxb7  , and here Black can try  18...Na6  19.Qf5  Qc5  20.Be5  , with the idea to eliminate the knight and give a mate. Black can still try the brilliant  20...Rb8  when we win with the even more brilliant  21.Ne4  . }
15. Qxd4 Nd7 { Black threatens ...e5 followed by ...Bc5! } 16. Re1
{ After  16...e5  17.Rxe5  White is doing great!   Black's best move is  16...hxg4  , we can reply with  17.Qb4  putting pressure on the b7-pawn, when after  17...Nb6  18.fxg4  White keeps a significant advantage. }
*

