1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The main move, and for a good reason! Black develops the bishop before closing the pawn chain with ...e6. }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  .  The latter allows us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Be4
{ Objectively, the best reply and the move suggested by L'Ami in his Chessable course on the Caro-Kann. }
5. f3 Bg6 6. e6
{ The third most popular move in the position. We immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop. We don't want to play the popular  6.h4  h5  7.e6  Qd6  when Black is threatening ...Qg3+ and White struggles to equalize. }
6... Qd6
{ A logical move, Black doesn't want to lock in the dark-squared bishop with  6...fxe6  , so it forces us to capture on f7. }
7. exf7+ Bxf7
{ When we reach this pawn structure, both sides have weaknesses. From Black's side, the e-pawn is weak. When Black can't trade the e-pawn, it will obstruct other pieces. On the other hand, White's pawns on the kingside are also weak, and f3 is not available for the knight. We plan to prevent Black from trading the e-pawn and castle queenside. }
8. Nc3 { Developing and preparing to castle queenside. } 8... Nd7
{ Black develops and prepares ...e5! } 9. f4
{ Preventing ...e5! It wasn't necessary to prevent ...e5 on the previous move since Black could only recapture with the queen, and we learned that after @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2pbpp/2pq4/3p4/3P2P1/2N2P2/PPP4P/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5  9.dxe5  Qxe5+  10.Nge2  , we would gain a tempo in development with Bf4. Since now after @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp2pbpp/2pq4/3p4/3P2P1/2N2P2/PPP4P/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nd7  Black was ready to recapture with ...Nxe5 it was necessary to prevent the ...e5 break with  9.f4  . }
9... g5 { Black insists on playing ...e5 and is willing to sacrifice a pawn. }
10. Nh3
{ Developing and putting pressure on the g5-pawn.  10.fxg5  e5  is also playable; however, Black has good compensation for the pawn. }
10... h6 { 10...gxf4  11.Bxf4  transposes to more or less the same position. }
11. Be3 { We get ready to play Qd2 and O-O-O. } 11... gxf4 12. Bxf4 e5 13. dxe5
Nxe5 14. Qe2 Bg7 15. O-O-O Ne7
{ 15...O-O-O  would be a mistake when after  16.Re1  Re8  17.Qe3!  White attacks the a7-pawn and gets an advantage. We can counter the fork ...d4 with Ne4, and White has a significant advantage due to the pin on the e5-knight. }
16. Ne4
{ We want to play Ne4-Ng3-Nh5, harassing the bishop or forcing a favorable trade. }
16... Qc7 17. Ng3 O-O-O 18. Nh5 Bxh5 19. gxh5
{ The position is equal with chances for both sides. We like to play Kb1, and we can place the rooks on the open e- and g-files and go for Nf2-Nd3. @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp1npb1p/2pq4/3p2p1/3P1PP1/2N4N/PPP4P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...gxf4  11.Bxf4  e5  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Qe2  Bg7  14.O-O-O  Ne7  15.Ne4  Qc7  16.Ng3  O-O-O  17.Nh5  Bxh5  18.gxh5  transposes to more or less the same position as here. It could be a slight disadvantage for Black that the pawn is on h7 since we can use the g5-square for the knight. }
