1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann, Black prepares to fight back in the center with ...d5. } 2. d4
{ We don't hesitate to grab the big center Black gave us. } 2... d5
{ Black's idea is to immediately fight back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the Advance variation, grabbing more space. We restrict Black's knight from developing to the natural f6-square. Grandmaster L'Ami, who made the Lifetime Repertoires: Caro-Kann on Chessable called the Advance Variation the big test against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5 4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  .  The latter allows us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Bg6 5. e6 fxe6 6. h4
{ In a Titled Tuesday match, GM Mamedyarov won a smooth game as his opponent already went wrong here by playing  7...Bf7  . }
6... h5
{ Many other moves have been played, but when Black allows us to play h5, the position is very good for us. }
7. Bd3 { We dominate the light squares. } 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 hxg4 9. Qg6+
{ We give the check and grab back the pawn. } 9... Kd7 10. Qxg4 Nf6 11. Qh3
{ Keeping an eye on the pinned e6-pawn. We threaten Nf3, Ne5, so Black has to defend against that. The computer also suggests  11.Qe2  as an alternative. I chose to recommend  11.Qh3  as we keep pressure on the pinned e6-pawn. }
11... c5 12. Nf3 { Threatening Ne5+. } 12... Nc6
{ Black has to defend against Ne5+. } 13. dxc5
{ We grab the pawn and challenge Black to win it back. This position could also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rn1q1bnr/pp1kp1p1/2p1p3/3p4/3P2QP/8/PPP2P2/RNB1K1NR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...c5  11.Nf3  Nc6  12.dxc5  Nf6  13.Qh3  . }
13... Qa5+ { Black gives a double attack and can win back the c5-pawn. } 14.
Nbd2 Qxc5 15. c3 { Defending against ...Qxc2. } 15... Qd6
{ Black somehow needs to activate the bishop, so they first want to protect the e6-pawn to subsequently move the king away to unpin the pawn and then slowly play ...e5! }
16. Nb3
{ We want to play Be3, O-O-O, Rg1, and have a fighting middlegame. White has good compensation for the pawn as the dark-squared bishop is still stuck. If Black unpins the pawn with  16...Ke8  , we can attack with  17.Ng5  e5  18.Qf5  when we dominate the light squares and have a better position.   Black's best move is  16...Ne4  when after  17.Rg1  g5!  18.Nxg5  Nxg5  19.Bxg5  Bh6  20.Qe3  We still keep some pressure. }
