3... Bf5 4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  .  The latter allows us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Bg6 5. e6 Qd6
{ Black threatens ...Qxe6 and forces us to trade the pawns. } 6. exf7+ Bxf7
{ We weaken the light-squares and create an outpost for our knight on e5! When we reach this pawn structure, both sides have weaknesses. From Black's side, the e-pawn is weak. When Black can't trade the e-pawn or move it forward, it will obstruct other pieces. For us, the g4-pawn can be a weakness. The pawn can come in handy, and we play g5 in some cases to stop the development of the knight. }
7. Nc3
{ This is a novelty. We play in the same style as in the  4...Be4  the variation here and prepare to castle queenside. We have a transposition to the position here, but with the pawn still on f2. A downside could be that the g4-pawn is not defended now; however, as the pawn is still on f2, we can also directly use the f3-square for the knight. All the details of how to play with the pawn on f2 or f3 are explained here. }
7... e5 8. Nf3
{ We want to place the knight on e5. The variation with  8.dxe5  Qxe5  9.Nge2  is less good here since Black will gain a tempo with ...Nf6 when our g4-pawn is undefended. }
8... e4 9. Ne5
{ Our knight is perfectly placed in the center. Trading it for the bishop would misplace Black's king and break their right to castle, so Black should still move the bishop. }
9... Be6 { Black prevents ...Nxf7! } 10. f3
{ We immediately want to trade Black's e4-pawn and open the position. } 10...
exf3
{ After  10...Nd7  11.Bf4  Nxe5  12.Bxe5  , we again have the idea that after  12...Qb4  13.a3  we can trap the queen after  13...Qxb2  14.Na4  .  White has a slight advantage after @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp4pp/2pqb3/3pB3/3Pp1P1/2N2P2/PPP4P/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qd7  13.fxe4  , and after  13...dxe4  , we can break open the position with  14.d5  Bxg4  15.Be2  Bxe2  16.Qxe2  With a fantastic position for White. }
11. Bf4
{ Is great for White threatening Ng6. After  11...Qb4  , we have the idea that  12.a3  Qxb2  13.Na4  traps the queen. }
