{ The Bayonet Attack is known to be one of the most aggressive and dynamic openings to fight the Caro-Kann and is also sound. A Bayonet Attack refers to an attack by advancing the knight's pawn. This is only the 5th most popular move in the position, so it has some serious surprise value. Also, in the following moves, we will frequently deviate from the most played lines and take our opponents down in unknown theory. Our idea is straightforward either Black has to retreat with  4...Bd7  and give up their Caro-Kann dream of having a bishop outside the pawn chain, or play  4...Be4  5.f3  Bg6  or  4...Bg6  .  The latter allows us to play  5.e6  aiming to bury the dark-squared bishop, which will have serious trouble developing after  5...fxe6  . }
4... Bd7
{ The third most popular move and a critical one. The problem for Black is when they play ...e6, they accept to have a bad 'French bishop' locked in within the pawn chain. Having the pawn on g4 benefits us since Black cannot use the f5-square for the knight or bishop. Nevertheless, having the pawn on g4 could be a significant drawback in case the position opens up, as the pawn can be weak, and also, the squares on the kingside are weakened. Therefore our strategy is to prevent Black's break with ...c5 and keep the position closed. }
5. Nc3
{ I also considered  5.c4  , but we are overextended with White, and Black is doing fine after  5...e6  6.Nc3  c5  when the position opens up and our g4-pawn becomes weak.  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2p5/3pP3/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Be3  would almost be the same as we transpose after  5...e6  6.Nc3  .   I chose to recommend @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1bpppp/2p5/3pP3/3P2P1/8/PPP2P1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  , as in the variation with  5...h5  , we can benefit from delaying the bishop's development after  6.gxh5  Bf5  7.Nge2  Bg4  when  8.Bg5  pins the e7-pawn. }
5... e6 6. Be3
{ The plan is prophylactic: we play against the ...c5-break, which Black inevitably should play at some point. }
6... c5
{ Black goes for the pawn break directly. This is risky as Black has difficulties holding on to the pawn. }
7. dxc5 Qc7 { Black attacks the c5 and e5-pawns. } 8. Nb5
{ This will force Black to give up the bishop pair. } 8... Bxb5 9. Bxb5+ Nc6
{ Black threatens ...Qa5+ to win the bishop. } 10. c3
{ Defending against ...Qa5+. } 10... Qxe5 11. Nf3 { Developing with tempo. }
11... Qc7 12. Qa4 { Increasing the pressure on the pinned c6-knight. } 12... a6
13. Nd4 { As the a-pawn is pinned, we can keep harassing the pinned knight. }
13... Ne7 14. O-O-O
{ We finish development and keep the queen on the kingside. } 14... O-O-O
{ Black has to castle queenside after  14...g6  15.Be2  , we are threatening Nb5 attacking the queen and getting ready to jump to d6. }
15. Be2
{ White has a comfortable position. After  15...e5  16.Nc2  g6  17.h4  , we start harassing the bishop with h5-h6. And when Black plays 17...h5  , we are happy to trade with  18.gxh5  gxh5  when our bishop keeps pressure on the h5-pawn. We have the same idea after  15...g6  16.Kb1  Bg7  17.h4  . }
*

